{"title_page": "Twin Cities and Western Railroad", "text_new": "{{Infobox rail\n|railroad_name   = Twin Cities and Western Railroad\n|marks           = TCWR\n|locale          = [[Minnesota]], [[South Dakota]]\n|start_year      = 1991\n|end_year        = present\n|hq_city         = [[Glencoe, Minnesota]]\n|gauge           = {{Railgauge|ussg}}\n|length          = {{convert|229|mi}}\n|website         = {{official website|http://tcwr.net}}\n|logo_filename   =\n|logo_size       =\n|image           = TCWR Train.jpg\n|image_caption   = A Twin Cities and Western Railroad train waits in downtown [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]].\n|system_map      = TCWR Map.png\n|map_size        = 240px\n|map_caption     = Twin Cities and Western Railroad trackage.  Solid lines are track owned by TCWR; dotted lines are TCWR trackage rights.\n}}\n\nThe '''Twin Cities and Western Railroad''' {{Reporting mark|TCWR}} is a [[rail transport|railroad]] operating in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Minnesota]] which started operations on July 27, 1991.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Edward |date=1996 |title=American Shortline Railway Guide, 5th Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3i6K_Nf9e2EC&printsec=frontcover&dq=American+Shortline+Railroad+guide&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6P-AVP-mE5S4ogTmpYCoAQ&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Twin%20Cities&f=false|location=Waukesha, Wisconsin |publisher=[[Kalmbach Publishing]]|page=316 |isbn=0-89024-290-9 |access-date=December 4, 2014 }}</ref>  Trackage includes the former [[Soo Line Railroad]] \"Ortonville Line\", originally built as the first part of the Pacific extension of the [[Milwaukee Road]].  This main line extends from [[Hopkins, Minnesota]] (a Western suburb of the [[Minneapolis \u2013 Saint Paul|Twin Cities]]) to [[Appleton, Minnesota]]. The line was originally built between Hopkins and [[Cologne, Minnesota|Cologne Minnesota]] in 1876 by Hastings and Dakota Railroad.  In 1913, the Milwaukee Road rerouted it, reducing the curves. The line was eventually extended to the Pacific.\n\nAs of 1991, the TCWR also has trackage rights over the [[BNSF Railway]] and the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]]. In 2012, the TCWR purchased the Sisseton Milbank Railroad and it now operates as a subsidiary of the Twin Cities and Western Railway.<ref>[http://tcwr.net/mpl/smrr-company-overview/ \"Sisseton Milbank Railroad Overview.\"] ''Twin Cities & Western Railroad Company.'' Retrieved: 22 March 2015.</ref>\n\nThe company is also affiliated with the [[Red River Valley and Western Railroad]] in [[North Dakota]], and the [[Minnesota Prairie Line]], which has a junction with the Twin Cities and Western in [[Norwood Young America, Minnesota]]. \n==Current routing==\nUntil Hiawatha Avenue ([[Minnesota State Highway 55]]) was reconstructed in the 1990s and plans for the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Hiawatha Line]] [[light rail]] service entered late stages, the Twin Cities and Western operated on Canadian Pacific's Bass Lake Subdivision through the 29th Street railway trench in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis]], now known as the [[Midtown Greenway]].  The tracks continued along the former Milwaukee Road [[Merriam Park Subdivision|Short Line]] into [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], where TC&W would access rail yards operated by Canadian Pacific, the [[Minnesota Commercial Railway]], and others.  As part of the Hiawatha project, the railroad's route to St Paul was moved from the 29th Street Corridor to the Kenilworth Corridor (former M&STL/C&NW track) to Cedar Lake Junction onto the BNSF just west of downtown Minneapolis. The re-route occurred August 1998.\n\nAfter the re-route onto to Kenilworth Corridor occurred in 1998, HCRRA constructed the Kenilworth Trail adjacent to the railroad track, using railroad right-of-way acquired from the Chicago North Western Railway by the [[Hennepin County Regional Railroad Authority]].<ref name=\"realignment-2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stlouispark.org/pdf/freight_rail_realignment_study.pdf|title=TCWR Freight Rail Realignment Study|publisher=Hennepin County Regional Railroad Authority/TKDA|date=November 18, 2009|accessdate=October 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718153108/http://www.stlouispark.org/pdf/freight_rail_realignment_study.pdf|archivedate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>  The Kenilworth alignment had first been built as part of the [[Minneapolis and St. Louis Railway]] and eventually became part of the [[Chicago and North Western Railway]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Electric Railways of Minnesota|author=Russell L. Olson|publisher=Minnesota Transportation Museum, Inc|year=1976}}</ref>  The Hennepin County Regional Rail Authority acquired the land (1984?) prior to when C&NW abandoned the line (1993?) .<ref name=\"realignment-2009\"/> The existing freight operation shares the corridor with the [[Kenilworth Trail]].\n\nThe temporary alignment was only expected to last five years and was proposed as a way to preserve the route for future transit.<ref name=\"realignment-2009\" />  It has been more than a decade since this alignment opened.  The connection is reaching the end of its lifespan and requires rehabilitation.<ref name=\"realignment-2009\" />\n\n==Planned changes==\nA rerouting of the line was re-examined in 2009 for the planned [[Southwest Corridor (Minnesota)|Southwest Corridor]] light-rail line.   Building the connection to the MN&S Subdivision was expected to cost about $48 million.<ref name=\"realignment-2009\"/>  A more detailed analysis was expected to be completed by the end of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mnsrailstudy.org/home|title=Background and Description of the Study|work=MN&S Rail Study|accessdate=October 8, 2010}}</ref> Because there was no freight rail engineering study done on the planned re-route of the freight rail route, and once the freight rail engineering study was completed in 2013, the impact of a safe re-route of freight rail was determined to negatively impact the local community, therefore the local community rejected freight rail reroute plans to the MN&S Subdivision in 2014.\n\n==Rolling stock and other properties==\nTC&W has 9 Caterpillar Generation II locomotives (4 [[EMD GP20|GP20C]]s, 3 [[EMD GP30|GP30C]]s, 2 [[GP15C]]s), 2 ex-KCC [[EMD GP39-2|GP39-2]]s, 1 [[CF7]] [[slug (railroad)|slug]] unit, 1 Paducah rebuilt [[EMD GP10|GP10]], 1 [[EMD SW1200|SW1200]], and 6 [[EMD GP38-2|GP38-2]]s. Trains typically run six days per week between the Twin Cities and Renville with two- or three-day-per-week service west of Renville to Milbank, SD.\n\nIn order to protect a potentially important shipping route, TC&W purchased the [[Dan Patch Line Bridge]] over the [[Minnesota River]] in [[Savage, Minnesota|Savage]].  TC&W has trackage rights over CP's MN&S Subdivision to reach Savage.<ref name=\"realignment-2009\"/>\n\n== Company officers ==\nPresidents of the TC&W have included:\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n* Dennis Shaffer, 1991 - 1993\n* William F. Drusch, 1993 - 2007.<ref name=\"PR-inside\">{{cite press release| publisher=Twin Cities & Western Railroad| date=2007-04-12| title=Twin Cities & Western Railroad Promotes Wegner to President}}</ref>\n* Mark J. Wegner, 2007 -present.<ref name=\"PR-inside\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Portal|Railways}}\n* [http://www.tcwr.net/ Twin Cities & Western Railroad] company site\n* [http://www.tcwr.net46.net Unofficial Twin Cities & Western Website]\n\n{{Twin Cities Railroads}}\n{{Minnesota railroads}}\n{{South Dakota railroads}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Twin Cities Western Railroad}}\n[[Category:Minnesota railroads]]\n[[Category:South Dakota railroads]]\n[[Category:Spin-offs of the Canadian Pacific Railway]]\n[[Category:Companies operating former Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad lines]]\n[[Category:Companies operating former Chicago and North Western Transportation Company lines<!--ex-M&StL-->]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rail\n|railroad_name   = Twin Cities and Western Railroad\n|marks           = TCWR\n|locale          = [[Minnesota]], [[South Dakota]]\n|start_year      = 1991\n|end_year        = present\n|hq_city         = [[Glencoe, Minnesota]]\n|gauge           = {{Railgauge|ussg}}\n|length          = {{convert|229|mi}}\n|website         = {{official website|http://tcwr.net}}\n|logo_filename   =\n|logo_size       =\n|image           = TCWR Train.jpg\n|image_caption   = A Twin Cities and Western Railroad train waits in downtown [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]].\n|system_map      = TCWR Map.png\n|map_size        = 240px\n|map_caption     = Twin Cities and Western Railroad trackage.  Solid lines are track owned by TCWR; dotted lines are TCWR trackage rights.\n}}\n\nThe '''Twin Cities and Western Railroad''' {{Reporting mark|TCWR}} is a [[rail transport|railroad]] operating in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Minnesota]] which started operations on July 27, 1991.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Edward |date=1996 |title=American Shortline Railway Guide, 5th Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3i6K_Nf9e2EC&printsec=frontcover&dq=American+Shortline+Railroad+guide&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6P-AVP-mE5S4ogTmpYCoAQ&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Twin%20Cities&f=false|location=Waukesha, Wisconsin |publisher=[[Kalmbach Publishing]]|page=316 |isbn=0-89024-290-9 |access-date=December 4, 2014 }}</ref>  Trackage includes the former [[Soo Line Railroad]] \"Ortonville Line\", originally built as the first part of the Pacific extension of the [[Milwaukee Road]].  This main line extends from [[Hopkins, Minnesota]] (a Western suburb of the [[Minneapolis \u2013 Saint Paul|Twin Cities]]) to [[Appleton, Minnesota]]. The line was originally built between Hopkins and [[Cologne, Minnesota|Cologne Minnesota]] in 1876 by Hastings and Dakota Railroad.  In 1913, the Milwaukee Road rerouted it, reducing the curves. The line was eventually extended to the Pacific.\n\nAs of 1991, the TCWR also has trackage rights over the [[BNSF Railway]] and the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]]. In 2012, the TCWR purchased the Sisseton Milbank Railroad and it now operates as a subsidiary of the Twin Cities and Western Railway.<ref>[http://tcwr.net/mpl/smrr-company-overview/ \"Sisseton Milbank Railroad Overview.\"] ''Twin Cities & Western Railroad Company.'' Retrieved: 22 March 2015.</ref>\n\nThe company is also affiliated with the [[Red River Valley and Western Railroad]] in [[North Dakota]], and the [[Minnesota Prairie Line]], which has a junction with the Twin Cities and Western in [[Norwood Young America, Minnesota]]. \n==Current routing==\nUntil Hiawatha Avenue ([[Minnesota State Highway 55]]) was reconstructed in the 1990s and plans for the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Hiawatha Line]] [[light rail]] service entered late stages, the Twin Cities and Western operated on Canadian Pacific's Bass Lake Subdivision through the 29th Street railway trench in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis]], now known as the [[Midtown Greenway]].  The tracks continued along the former Milwaukee Road [[Merriam Park Subdivision|Short Line]] into [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], where TC&W would access rail yards operated by Canadian Pacific, the [[Minnesota Commercial Railway]], and others.  As part of the Hiawatha project, the railroad's route to St Paul was moved from the 29th Street Corridor to the Kenilworth Corridor (former M&STL/C&NW track) to Cedar Lake Junction onto the BNSF just west of downtown Minneapolis. The re-route occurred August 1998.\n\nAfter the re-route onto to Kenilworth Corridor occurred in 1998, HCRRA constructed the Kenilworth Trail adjacent to the railroad track, using railroad right-of-way acquired from the Chicago North Western Railway by the [[Hennepin County Regional Railroad Authority]].<ref name=\"realignment-2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stlouispark.org/pdf/freight_rail_realignment_study.pdf|title=TCWR Freight Rail Realignment Study|publisher=Hennepin County Regional Railroad Authority/TKDA|date=November 18, 2009|accessdate=October 8, 2010|url-statu