{"title_page": "Ouvrage Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel", "text_new": "{{Infobox Military Structure\n|name=Ouvrage Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel\n|partof=[[Maginot Line]]\n|location=Northeast [[France]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|49.0525|7.50511|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|map_type = France\n|map_size = 280\n|type=\n|code=\n|built=\n|builder=CORF\n|materials=Concrete, steel, deep excavation\n|height=\n|used=Abandoned\n|demolished=\n|condition=\n|ownership=French Army\n|open_to_public=\n|controlledby=France\n|garrison=\n|current_commander=\n|commanders=\n|occupants=\n|battles=[[Battle of France]], [[Lorraine Campaign]], [[Battle of the Bulge]]\n|events=\n}}\n{{Maginot Line Infobox\n|localisation=\n|type=PO\n|year=\n|sector=[[Fortified Sector of the Vosges]]\n|sub-sector=Philippsbourg\n|number=O 450, ''Ouvrage C''\n|regiment=154th Fortress Infantry Regiment (RIF)\n|blocks=7\n|entrance=\n|strength=7 officers, 197 enlisted\n|picture=\n|caption=\n}}\n\n'''Ouvrage Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel''' is a large work ''gros ouvrage'' of the [[Maginot Line]], located near [[Bitche]] in the [[France|French]] ''d\u00e9partement'' of [[Moselle (d\u00e9partement)|Moselle]].  Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel is adjoined by ''gros ouvrage'' [[Ouvrage Otterbiel|Otterbiel]] to the west and ''petit ouvrage'' [[Ouvrage Lembach|Lembach]] at some distance to the east, and faces the [[Germany|German]] frontier. It was part of the [[Fortified Sector of the Vosges]].\n\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel comprises two separate entrance blocks for ammunition and personnel, three infantry blocks, one artillery block and one observation block. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel saw no significant action in the [[Battle of France]], and limited action during the 1944/45 [[Lorraine Campaign]]. It was renovated for use during the [[Cold War]]. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel is now unused, on restricted military land.\n\n== Design and construction ==\nThe site was surveyed by the Commission d'Organisation des R\u00e9gions Fortifi\u00e9es (CORF), the Maginot Line's design and construction agency; Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was approved for construction in August 1931. The ''petit ouvrage''{{#tag:ref|English-language sources use the French term ''ouvrage'' as the preferred term for the Maginot positions, in preference to \"fort\", a term usually reserved for older fortifications with passive defensives in the form of walls and ditches.<ref name=\"kaufmann1\">Kaufmann 2006, p. 13</ref> The literal translation of ''ouvrage'' in the sense of a fortification in English is \"work.\" A ''gros ouvrage'' is a large fortification with a significant artillery component, while a ''petit ouvrage'' is smaller, with lighter arms.<ref>Kaufmann 2006, p. 20</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} is a typical ''gros ouvrage'' of the smaller sort, with separate personnel and munitions entries a few hundred meters to the rear of the combat blocks, which are sited on an eminence controlling the terrain to the north. A second phase of construction, planned but not carried out, envisioned the addition of an 81mm mortar turret and an additional 75mm gun turret.<ref name=\"hetou3-1\">Mary, Tome 3, p. 130</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel comprises two entrance blocks, three infantry blocks, one artillery block and an observation block. The munitions and personnel entries are located to the rear of the compactly arranged combat blocks.  A small barracks and ''usine'' or service area are located near the personnel entry. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel lacks a main \"M1\" magazine, usually provided in a ''gros ouvrage''. From the junction of the entry galleries a gallery runs at an average depth of {{convert|30|m|ft}} to the combat blocks.\n*'''Block 1''': Infantry block with one retractable twin machine gun turret and one [[GFM cloche|automatic rifle cloche (GFM)]].<ref name=\"fortiffbe1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4288|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 1|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 2''': Infantry block with two GFM cloches, two [[JM cloche|twin machine gun cloches]], one twin machine gun embrasure and one machine gun (JM)/[[AC 47 anti-tank gun|47mm anti-tank gun]] embrasure (JM/AC47).<ref name=\"fortiffbe2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4289|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 2|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 3''': Infantry block with two GFM cloches, one [[JM cloche|twin machine gun cloche]], one twin machine gun embrasure and one JM/AC 47 embrasure.<ref name=\"fortiffbe3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4290|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 3|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 4''': Artillery block with one GFM cloche, one [[VDP cloche|observation cloche (VDP)]], one [[LG cloche|grenade launcher cloche (LG)]] and one 75 mm gun turret (model 33).<ref name=\"fortiffbe4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4291|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 4|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 5''': Observation block with one GFM cloche and one GFM/observation cloche.<ref name=\"fortiffbe5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4292|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 5|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Personnel entry''': Shaft-style entry block with one GFM cloche and one JM/AC47 embrasure.<ref name=\"fortiffbe1a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4295|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Entr\u00e9e hommes|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Munitions entry''': Direct entry block with two GFM cloches and one JM/AC47 embrasure.<ref name=\"fortiffbe1b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4296|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Entr\u00e9e munitions|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n=== Casemates and shelters ===\nA series of detached [[casemate]]s and infantry shelters are in the vicinity of Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel, including\n\n* '''Abri du D\u00e9p\u00f4t''': Subsurface ''abri-caverne''{{#tag:ref|An ''abri'' is an infantry shelter, sometimes underground or under earth cover. An ''abri'' in the main Maginot Line often closely resembles a casemate, but is more lightly armed and can hold more occupants.<ref>Kaufmann 2006, p. 14</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} with two GFM cloches\n* '''Abri de Wolfschlachen''': Subsurface ''abri-caverne'' with two GFM cloches.<ref name=\"hetou3-1\"/>\n\nAdditionally, the space between Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel and Lembach, its neighbor to the east, is filled by more than forty casemates and blockhouses along the river Schwartzbach and across the ridge to the [[Sauer|Sauer river]].<ref name=\"hetou3-1\"/>\n\n== Manning ==\nThe 1939 manning of the ''ouvrage'' under the command of Commandant Fabre comprised 179 men and 7 officers of the 154th Fortress Infantry Regiment and the 168th Position Artillery Regiment.<ref name=\"hetou3-1\"/> The units were under the umbrella of the 5th Army.<ref>Mary, Tome 3, p. 122</ref> The nearby Casernement de Neunhoffen provided peacetime above-ground barracks and support services to Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel and other positions in the area.<ref>Mary, Tome 3, p. 129</ref><ref name=\"dkpl0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.darkplaces.org/Frankreich/WW2/Ligne_Maginot/SF_des_Vosges/SF_des_Vosges.html|title=Festungsabschnitt Vogesen |last=Wahl|first=J.B.|publisher=darkplaces.org|language=German|accessdate=9 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n:''See [[Fortified Sector of the Vosges]] for a broader discussion of the Vosges sector of the Maginot Line.''\n=== 1940 ===\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel saw relatively little action in 1940 compared to its neighbors, and surrendered to the Germans with the rest of the Bitche fortifications on 30 June 1940. Its chief action was artillery support of the line of casemates to the east of Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel which were attacked by the German [[215th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|215th Infantry Division]] on 19 June 1940, breaking the French line.<ref>Mary, Tome 3, pp. 233, 237</ref><ref name=\"romanych1\">Romanych, pp. 75\u201376|</ref>\n\n=== 1944 and 1945 ===\nAt the end of November 1944 the [[United States Army Europe|U.S. Seventh Army]] under General [[Alexander Patch]] had reached the Vosges region. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was occupied by elements of the German 25th Panzer Grenadier Division.<ref name=\"usaww2-1\">{{cite web|last=Clarke|first=Jeremy|title=On to the Siegfried Line|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-E-Riviera/USA-E-Riviera-26.html|work=The U.S. Army in World War II|publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]]|accessdate=9 June 2010|pages=471\u2013475}}</ref> Otterbiel and Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel were to be the next positions to be attacked by the [[100th Infantry Division (United States)|U.S. 100th Infantry Division]], but the planned operation was disrupted by the [[Battle of the Bulge]]. The Seventh Army withdrew to cover areas vacated by the [[United States Army Central|U.S. Third Army]], which moved to confront the German offensive.<ref name=\"milhisto1\">{{cite web|last=Dickerson|first=Bryan J.|title=The US Army vs. the Maginot Line|url=http://www.militaryhistoryonline.com/wwii/articles/maginotline.aspx|publisher=Military History Online|accessdate=8 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe 100th returned in March 1945 attacked the area on a broad front. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was lightly defended, and the Americans, backed up by heavy artillery, were able to capture Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel and the ''Ensemble de Bitche'' with few casualties.<ref name=\"milhisto1\"/>\n\n=== Cold War ===\nFollowing World War II, interest revived in the use of the Maginot Line to defend against a possible Soviet advance through southern Germany.  Funds were allocated for restoration of the ''gros ouvrages'', but work was limited to restoration of systems and improvements to existing armament, with work completed by 1953.<ref name=\"Mary, Tome 5, p. 161\">Mary, Tome 5, p. 161</ref> By 1953, Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel had been designated part of the ''M\u00f2le de Bitche'', a strongpoint in the northeastern defenses against Soviet attack.<ref name=\"Mary, Tome 5, p. 161\"/> By the late 1950s interest in fixed fortifications was waning after  France developed a nuclear deterrent.  The money needed to maintain and upgrade the fortifications was diverted for the nuclear programs. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was not manned or maintained after the early 1970s.<ref>Mary, Tome 5, p. 173</ref>\n\n== Present condition ==\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel is on military land and is not accessible to the public.<ref name=\"donnell1\">{{cite web|last=Donnell|first=Clayton|title=Off the Beaten Path|url=http://webspace.webring.com/people/gb/bunkernut/beaten.html}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Maginot Line ouvrages|List of all works on Maginot Line]]\n* [[Siegfried Line]]\n* [[Atlantic Wall]]\n* [[Czechoslovak border fortifications]]\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Allcorn, William. ''The Maginot Line 1928-45.'' Oxford: Osprey Publishing, 2003. {{ISBN|1-84176-646-1}}\n*Kaufmann, J.E. and Kaufmann, H.W. ''Fortress France: The Maginot Line and French Defenses in World War II'', Stackpole Books, 2006. {{ISBN|0-275-98345-5}}\n*Kaufmann, J.E., Kaufmann, H.W., Jancovi\u010d-Poto\u010dnik, A. and Lang, P. ''The Maginot Line: History and Guide'', Pen and Sword, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84884-068-3}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 1.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2001. {{ISBN|2-908182-88-2}} {{in lang|fr}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 2.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2003. {{ISBN|2-908182-97-1}} {{in lang|fr}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 3.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2003. {{ISBN|2-913903-88-6}} {{in lang|fr}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 5.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2009. {{ISBN|978-2-35250-127-5}} {{in lang|fr}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.alsacemaginot.com/pages/racine-decouverte-vosges-gh L'ouvrage du Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel] at alsacemaginot.com {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.lignemaginot.com/ligne/sf-vosge/hohe/index.htm Ouvrage du Grand Hoh\u00e9kirkel] at lignemaginot.com {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?page=g15 Grand Hoh\u00e9kirkel (gros ouvrage du)] at fortiff.be {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Maginot Line list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grand-Hohekirkel, Ouvrage}}\n[[Category:Maginot Line]]\n[[Category:Fortified sector of the Vosges|GRAN]]\n[[Category:M\u00f4le de Bitche|GRAN]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Military Structure\n|name=Ouvrage Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel\n|partof=[[Maginot Line]]\n|location=Northeast [[France]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|49.0525|7.50511|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|map_type = France\n|map_size = 280\n|type=\n|code=\n|built=\n|builder=CORF\n|materials=Concrete, steel, deep excavation\n|height=\n|used=Abandoned\n|demolished=\n|condition=\n|ownership=French Army\n|open_to_public=\n|controlledby=France\n|garrison=\n|current_commander=\n|commanders=\n|occupants=\n|battles=[[Battle of France]], [[Lorraine Campaign]], [[Battle of the Bulge]]\n|events=\n}}\n{{Maginot Line Infobox\n|localisation=\n|type=PO\n|year=\n|sector=[[Fortified Sector of the Vosges]]\n|sub-sector=Philippsbourg\n|number=O 450, ''Ouvrage C''\n|regiment=154th Fortress Infantry Regiment (RIF)\n|blocks=7\n|entrance=\n|strength=7 officers, 197 enlisted\n|picture=\n|caption=\n}}\n\n'''Ouvrage Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel''' is a ''petit ouvrage'' of the [[Maginot Line]], located near [[Bitche]] in the [[France|French]] ''d\u00e9partement'' of [[Moselle (d\u00e9partement)|Moselle]].  Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel is adjoined by ''gros ouvrage'' [[Ouvrage Otterbiel|Otterbiel]] to the west and ''petit ouvrage'' [[Ouvrage Lembach|Lembach]] at some distance to the east, and faces the [[Germany|German]] frontier. It was part of the [[Fortified Sector of the Vosges]].\n\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel comprises two separate entrance blocks for ammunition and personnel, three infantry blocks, one artillery block and one observation block. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel saw no significant action in the [[Battle of France]], and limited action during the 1944/45 [[Lorraine Campaign]]. It was renovated for use during the [[Cold War]]. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel is now unused, on restricted military land.\n\n== Design and construction ==\nThe site was surveyed by the Commission d'Organisation des R\u00e9gions Fortifi\u00e9es (CORF), the Maginot Line's design and construction agency; Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was approved for construction in August 1931. The ''petit ouvrage''{{#tag:ref|English-language sources use the French term ''ouvrage'' as the preferred term for the Maginot positions, in preference to \"fort\", a term usually reserved for older fortifications with passive defensives in the form of walls and ditches.<ref name=\"kaufmann1\">Kaufmann 2006, p. 13</ref> The literal translation of ''ouvrage'' in the sense of a fortification in English is \"work.\" A ''gros ouvrage'' is a large fortification with a significant artillery component, while a ''petit ouvrage'' is smaller, with lighter arms.<ref>Kaufmann 2006, p. 20</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} is a typical ''gros ouvrage'' of the smaller sort, with separate personnel and munitions entries a few hundred meters to the rear of the combat blocks, which are sited on an eminence controlling the terrain to the north. A second phase of construction, planned but not carried out, envisioned the addition of an 81mm mortar turret and an additional 75mm gun turret.<ref name=\"hetou3-1\">Mary, Tome 3, p. 130</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel comprises two entrance blocks, three infantry blocks, one artillery block and an observation block. The munitions and personnel entries are located to the rear of the compactly arranged combat blocks.  A small barracks and ''usine'' or service area are located near the personnel entry. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel lacks a main \"M1\" magazine, usually provided in a ''gros ouvrage''. From the junction of the entry galleries a gallery runs at an average depth of {{convert|30|m|ft}} to the combat blocks.\n*'''Block 1''': Infantry block with one retractable twin machine gun turret and one [[GFM cloche|automatic rifle cloche (GFM)]].<ref name=\"fortiffbe1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4288|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 1|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 2''': Infantry block with two GFM cloches, two [[JM cloche|twin machine gun cloches]], one twin machine gun embrasure and one machine gun (JM)/[[AC 47 anti-tank gun|47mm anti-tank gun]] embrasure (JM/AC47).<ref name=\"fortiffbe2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4289|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 2|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 3''': Infantry block with two GFM cloches, one [[JM cloche|twin machine gun cloche]], one twin machine gun embrasure and one JM/AC 47 embrasure.<ref name=\"fortiffbe3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4290|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 3|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 4''': Artillery block with one GFM cloche, one [[VDP cloche|observation cloche (VDP)]], one [[LG cloche|grenade launcher cloche (LG)]] and one 75mm gun embrasure.<ref name=\"fortiffbe4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4291|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 4|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Block 5''': Observation block with one GFM cloche and one GFM/observation cloche.<ref name=\"fortiffbe5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4292|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Bloc 5|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Personnel entry''': Shaft-style entry block with one GFM cloche and one JM/AC47 embrasure.<ref name=\"fortiffbe1a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4295|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Entr\u00e9e hommes|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*'''Munitions entry''': Direct entry block with two GFM cloches and one JM/AC47 embrasure.<ref name=\"fortiffbe1b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?p=4296|title=Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel (go du) Entr\u00e9e munitions|last=Puelinckx|first=Jean|year=2010|work=Index de la Ligne Maginot|publisher=fortiff.be|language=French|accessdate=9 June 2010|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n=== Casemates and shelters ===\nA series of detached [[casemate]]s and infantry shelters are in the vicinity of Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel, including\n\n* '''Abri du D\u00e9p\u00f4t''': Subsurface ''abri-caverne''{{#tag:ref|An ''abri'' is an infantry shelter, sometimes underground or under earth cover. An ''abri'' in the main Maginot Line often closely resembles a casemate, but is more lightly armed and can hold more occupants.<ref>Kaufmann 2006, p. 14</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} with two GFM cloches\n* '''Abri de Wolfschlachen''': Subsurface ''abri-caverne'' with two GFM cloches.<ref name=\"hetou3-1\"/>\n\nAdditionally, the space between Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel and Lembach, its neighbor to the east, is filled by more than forty casemates and blockhouses along the river Schwartzbach and across the ridge to the [[Sauer|Sauer river]].<ref name=\"hetou3-1\"/>\n\n== Manning ==\nThe 1939 manning of the ''ouvrage'' under the command of Commandant Fabre comprised 179 men and 7 officers of the 154th Fortress Infantry Regiment and the 168th Position Artillery Regiment.<ref name=\"hetou3-1\"/> The units were under the umbrella of the 5th Army.<ref>Mary, Tome 3, p. 122</ref> The nearby Casernement de Neunhoffen provided peacetime above-ground barracks and support services to Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel and other positions in the area.<ref>Mary, Tome 3, p. 129</ref><ref name=\"dkpl0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.darkplaces.org/Frankreich/WW2/Ligne_Maginot/SF_des_Vosges/SF_des_Vosges.html|title=Festungsabschnitt Vogesen |last=Wahl|first=J.B.|publisher=darkplaces.org|language=German|accessdate=9 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n:''See [[Fortified Sector of the Vosges]] for a broader discussion of the Vosges sector of the Maginot Line.''\n=== 1940 ===\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel saw relatively little action in 1940 compared to its neighbors, and surrendered to the Germans with the rest of the Bitche fortifications on 30 June 1940. Its chief action was artillery support of the line of casemates to the east of Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel which were attacked by the German [[215th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|215th Infantry Division]] on 19 June 1940, breaking the French line.<ref>Mary, Tome 3, pp. 233, 237</ref><ref name=\"romanych1\">Romanych, pp. 75\u201376|</ref>\n\n=== 1944 and 1945 ===\nAt the end of November 1944 the [[United States Army Europe|U.S. Seventh Army]] under General [[Alexander Patch]] had reached the Vosges region. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was occupied by elements of the German 25th Panzer Grenadier Division.<ref name=\"usaww2-1\">{{cite web|last=Clarke|first=Jeremy|title=On to the Siegfried Line|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-E-Riviera/USA-E-Riviera-26.html|work=The U.S. Army in World War II|publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]]|accessdate=9 June 2010|pages=471\u2013475}}</ref> Otterbiel and Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel were to be the next positions to be attacked by the [[100th Infantry Division (United States)|U.S. 100th Infantry Division]], but the planned operation was disrupted by the [[Battle of the Bulge]]. The Seventh Army withdrew to cover areas vacated by the [[United States Army Central|U.S. Third Army]], which moved to confront the German offensive.<ref name=\"milhisto1\">{{cite web|last=Dickerson|first=Bryan J.|title=The US Army vs. the Maginot Line|url=http://www.militaryhistoryonline.com/wwii/articles/maginotline.aspx|publisher=Military History Online|accessdate=8 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe 100th returned in March 1945 attacked the area on a broad front. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was lightly defended, and the Americans, backed up by heavy artillery, were able to capture Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel and the ''Ensemble de Bitche'' with few casualties.<ref name=\"milhisto1\"/>\n\n=== Cold War ===\nFollowing World War II, interest revived in the use of the Maginot Line to defend against a possible Soviet advance through southern Germany.  Funds were allocated for restoration of the ''gros ouvrages'', but work was limited to restoration of systems and improvements to existing armament, with work completed by 1953.<ref name=\"Mary, Tome 5, p. 161\">Mary, Tome 5, p. 161</ref> By 1953, Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel had been designated part of the ''M\u00f2le de Bitche'', a strongpoint in the northeastern defenses against Soviet attack.<ref name=\"Mary, Tome 5, p. 161\"/> By the late 1950s interest in fixed fortifications was waning after  France developed a nuclear deterrent.  The money needed to maintain and upgrade the fortifications was diverted for the nuclear programs. Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel was not manned or maintained after the early 1970s.<ref>Mary, Tome 5, p. 173</ref>\n\n== Present condition ==\nGrand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel is on military land and is not accessible to the public.<ref name=\"donnell1\">{{cite web|last=Donnell|first=Clayton|title=Off the Beaten Path|url=http://webspace.webring.com/people/gb/bunkernut/beaten.html}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Maginot Line ouvrages|List of all works on Maginot Line]]\n* [[Siegfried Line]]\n* [[Atlantic Wall]]\n* [[Czechoslovak border fortifications]]\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Allcorn, William. ''The Maginot Line 1928-45.'' Oxford: Osprey Publishing, 2003. {{ISBN|1-84176-646-1}}\n*Kaufmann, J.E. and Kaufmann, H.W. ''Fortress France: The Maginot Line and French Defenses in World War II'', Stackpole Books, 2006. {{ISBN|0-275-98345-5}}\n*Kaufmann, J.E., Kaufmann, H.W., Jancovi\u010d-Poto\u010dnik, A. and Lang, P. ''The Maginot Line: History and Guide'', Pen and Sword, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84884-068-3}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 1.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2001. {{ISBN|2-908182-88-2}} {{in lang|fr}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 2.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2003. {{ISBN|2-908182-97-1}} {{in lang|fr}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 3.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2003. {{ISBN|2-913903-88-6}} {{in lang|fr}}\n*Mary, Jean-Yves; Hohnadel, Alain; Sicard, Jacques. ''Hommes et Ouvrages de la Ligne Maginot, Tome 5.'' Paris, Histoire & Collections, 2009. {{ISBN|978-2-35250-127-5}} {{in lang|fr}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.alsacemaginot.com/pages/racine-decouverte-vosges-gh L'ouvrage du Grand-Hoh\u00e9kirkel] at alsacemaginot.com {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.lignemaginot.com/ligne/sf-vosge/hohe/index.htm Ouvrage du Grand Hoh\u00e9kirkel] at lignemaginot.com {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.fortiff.be/maginot/index.php?page=g15 Grand Hoh\u00e9kirkel (gros ouvrage du)] at fortiff.be {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Maginot Line list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grand-Hohekirkel, Ouvrage}}\n[[Category:Maginot Line]]\n[[Category:Fortified sector of the Vosges|GRAN]]\n[[Category:M\u00f4le de Bitche|GRAN]]\n", "name_user": "81.161.67.22", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(PO to GO, 75mm tourelle.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ouvrage_Grand-Hoh%C3%A9kirkel"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy O'Dea", "text_new": "[[File:Jimmy_O'Dea.png|thumb|right|Publicity still]]\n'''James Augustine O'Dea''' (26 April 1899 &ndash; 7 January 1965) was an Irish actor and comedian.\n\n==Life==\nJimmy O'Dea was born at 11 Lower Bridge Street, [[Dublin]], to James O'Dea, an ironmonger, and Martha O'Gorman, who kept a small toy shop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/728b716358642|title=General Registrar's Office|last=|first=|date=|website=IrishGenealogy.ie|publisher=|access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref> He was one of 11 children. His father had a shop in [[Capel Street]]. He was educated at the [[Irish Christian Brothers]] [[O'Connell School]] in North Richmond Street, Dublin, where a classmate was future [[Taoiseach]] [[Se\u00e1n Lemass]], by the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]] at [[Blackrock College]], and by the [[Jesuits]] at [[Belvedere College]].<ref name=\"name1\">''The Irish Times'', \"Jimmy O'Dea dies after 40 years on the Irish stage\", 8 January 1965</ref> From a young age he was interested in taking to the stage; he co-founded an amateur acting group, the Kilronan Players, in 1917. But his father would not hear of it. O'Dea was apprenticed to an optician in [[Edinburgh, Scotland]], where he qualified as an optician.<ref name=od/>\n\nHe returned to Dublin where, aged 21, he set up his own business which he was, eventually, to give to his sister, Rita. In his spare time he took part in amateur productions of Ibsen and Chekhov. From 1920 he was in the Irish theatre in Hardwicke Street working with actor-producer [[John McDonagh]]. After working in plays by [[George Bernard Shaw|Shaw]] for a few years he rejoined McDonagh in revues, the first of which, ''Dublin To-Night'', was produced at the [[Queen's Theatre, Dublin|Queen's Theatre]] in 1924. In 1927 he took to the stage full-time.<ref name=od>{{cite book|last=Boylan|first=Henry|year=1998|title=A Dictionary of Irish Biography, 3rd Edition|page=314|location=Dublin|publisher=Gill and MacMillan|isbn=0-7171-2945-4}}</ref> In 1928, this company's first production ''Here We Are'' won international acclaim, and in December of the same year it produced its first Christmas Pantomime, ''Sinbad the Sailor''.\n\nO'Dea formed a partnership with [[Harry O'Donovan]] (died 3 November 1973) whom he first met in a production of ''[[You Never Can Tell (play)|You Never Can Tell]]'' in 1924. Their first show was ''Look Who's Here'' at [[Queen's Theatre, Dublin|Queen's]]. For more than two decades beginning in 1929 the duo produced two shows a year in Dublin, first in the [[Olympia Theatre, Dublin|Olympia Theatre]], then in the [[Gaiety Theatre, Dublin|Gaiety]].<ref>''Irish Times'', 5 January 1950</ref> They created O'Dea's most famous character, \"Mrs. Biddy Mulligan\".<ref name=od/> The role drew on Jimmy's previous manifestations as \"Dames\" in Variety performances and pantomimes. Biddy Mulligan was the representation (caricature, parody and stereotype) of a Dublin street-seller, with all the working-class repartee, wisdom and failings implicit. He made a number of recordings of sketches starring Mrs. Mulligan.<ref>''Irish Times'', 6 November 1931</ref> Biddy Mulligan is referenced in many Dublin music hall songs such as \"[[Biddy Mulligan the Pride of the Coombe]]\", \"Daffy the Belle of the Coombe\" and \"The Charladies' Ball\".\n\nO'Dea made some film appearances, such as ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]'' (1959) in which he played King Brian of the little people and ''[[Johnny Nobody]]'' (1961).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47894222|title=The search for an Aussie leprechaun fan|first=Amy|last=Stewart|date=April 14, 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6ada3bea|title=Johnny Nobody (1961)|website=BFI}}</ref> He also had a successful career in pantomime and toured Ireland and England many times, and is much associated with actress [[Maureen Potter]] (1925-2004), with whom he often partnered.\n\nO'Dea was also a prolific songwriter in his day. Many of his songs are still well known to this day, some of them having been sung and recorded by Dublin singer [[Frank Harte]]. {{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}<ref>https://www.theballadeers.com/ire/fh_1987_dac.htm</ref><ref>http://www.fresnostate.edu/folklore/ballads/OLoc230A.html</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Dea married Ursula Doyle. Maureen Potter was bridesmaid.<ref>{{Citation|last=Report|first=|title=Jimmy O'Dea|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|page=4|date=25 September 1959}}</ref> [[Se\u00e1n Lemass]] was best-man; he would also give the valedictory oration at O'Dea's funeral in 1965. Jimmy O\u2019Dea had one child - Christine O\u2019Dea - who married Ursula Doyle\u2019s brother Noel Doyle. Christine lives in Toronto.\n\n==Death==\nJimmy O'Dea died at [[Dr Steevens' Hospital]], Dublin, aged 65, on January 6, 1965.<ref name=\"name1\"/>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Jimmy Boy]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[Cheer Boys Cheer]]'' (1939)\n* ''[[Let's Be Famous]]'' (1939)\n* ''[[The Rising of the Moon (film)|The Rising of the Moon]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]'' (1959)\n\n==Recordings==\nWith Harry O'Donovan:\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan nearly wins the Sweep\" E.3694 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan in London\" E.3895 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan at the telephone\" E.3663 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan at the talkies\" E.3764 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan at the racecourse\" E.3763 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan in the tram\" E.3764 Parlophone\n*\"The Irish Schoolmaster\" E.3634 Parlophone\n*\"Sixpence each way\" E.3634 Parlophone\n*\"Biddy Mulligan\" E 3817 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan, Smuggler\" \n*\"The Charladies' Ball\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0640618|name=Jimmy O'Dea}}\n*[http://dublinopinion.com/2008/06/09/jimmy-jimmy Jimmy O'Dea profile at Dublin Opinion website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odea, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish male comedians]]\n[[Category:Irish male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Pantomime]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Belvedere College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Blackrock College]]\n[[Category:20th-century comedians]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Jimmy_O'Dea.png|thumb|right|Publicity still]]\n'''James Augustine O'Dea''' (26 April 1899 &ndash; 7 January 1965) was an Irish actor and comedian.\n\n==Life==\nJimmy O'Dea was born at 11 Lower Bridge Street, [[Dublin]], to James O'Dea, an ironmonger, and Martha O'Gorman, who kept a small toy shop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/728b716358642|title=General Registrar's Office|last=|first=|date=|website=IrishGenealogy.ie|publisher=|access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref> He was one of 11 children. His father had a shop in [[Capel Street]]. He was educated at the [[Irish Christian Brothers]] [[O'Connell School]] in North Richmond Street, Dublin, where a classmate was future [[Taoiseach]] [[Se\u00e1n Lemass]], by the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]] at [[Blackrock College]], and by the [[Jesuits]] at [[Belvedere College]].<ref name=\"name1\">''The Irish Times'', \"Jimmy O'Dea dies after 40 years on the Irish stage\", 8 January 1965</ref> From a young age he was interested in taking to the stage; he co-founded an amateur acting group, the Kilronan Players, in 1917. But his father would not hear of it. O'Dea was apprenticed to an optician in [[Edinburgh, Scotland]], where he qualified as an optician.<ref name=od/>\n\nHe returned to Dublin where, aged 21, he set up his own business which he was, eventually, to give to his sister, Rita. In his spare time he took part in amateur productions of Ibsen and Chekhov. From 1920 he was in the Irish theatre in Hardwicke Street working with actor-producer [[John McDonagh]]. After working in plays by [[George Bernard Shaw|Shaw]] for a few years he rejoined McDonagh in revues, the first of which, ''Dublin To-Night'', was produced at the [[Queen's Theatre, Dublin|Queen's Theatre]] in 1924. In 1927 he took to the stage full-time.<ref name=od>{{cite book|last=Boylan|first=Henry|year=1998|title=A Dictionary of Irish Biography, 3rd Edition|page=314|location=Dublin|publisher=Gill and MacMillan|isbn=0-7171-2945-4}}</ref> In 1928, this company's first production ''Here We Are'' won international acclaim, and in December of the same year it produced its first Christmas Pantomime, ''Sinbad the Sailor''.\n\nO'Dea formed a partnership with [[Harry O'Donovan]] (died 3 November 1973) whom he first met in a production of ''[[You Never Can Tell (play)|You Never Can Tell]]'' in 1924. Their first show was ''Look Who's Here'' at [[Queen's Theatre, Dublin|Queen's]]. For more than two decades beginning in 1929 the duo produced two shows a year in Dublin, first in the [[Olympia Theatre, Dublin|Olympia Theatre]], then in the [[Gaiety Theatre, Dublin|Gaiety]].<ref>''Irish Times'', 5 January 1950</ref> They created O'Dea's most famous character, \"Mrs. Biddy Mulligan\".<ref name=od/> The role drew on Jimmy's previous manifestations as \"Dames\" in Variety performances and pantomimes. Biddy Mulligan was the representation (caricature, parody and stereotype) of a Dublin street-seller, with all the working-class repartee, wisdom and failings implicit. He made a number of recordings of sketches starring Mrs. Mulligan.<ref>''Irish Times'', 6 November 1931</ref> Biddy Mulligan is referenced in many Dublin music hall songs such as \"[[Biddy Mulligan the Pride of the Coombe]]\", \"Daffy the Belle of the Coombe\" and \"The Charladies' Ball\".\n\nO'Dea made some film appearances, such as ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]'' (1959) in which he played King Brian of the little people and ''[[Johnny Nobody]]'' (1961).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47894222|title=The search for an Aussie leprechaun fan|first=Amy|last=Stewart|date=April 14, 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6ada3bea|title=Johnny Nobody (1961)|website=BFI}}</ref> He also had a successful career in pantomime and toured Ireland and England many times, and is much associated with actress [[Maureen Potter]] (1925-2004), with whom he often partnered.\n\nO'Dea was also a prolific songwriter in his day. Many of his songs are still well known to this day, some of them having been sung and recorded by Dublin singer [[Frank Harte]]. {{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Dea married Ursula Doyle. Maureen Potter was bridesmaid.<ref>{{Citation|last=Report|first=|title=Jimmy O'Dea|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|page=4|date=25 September 1959}}</ref> [[Se\u00e1n Lemass]] was best-man; he would also give the valedictory oration at O'Dea's funeral in 1965. Jimmy O\u2019Dea had one child - Christine O\u2019Dea - who married Ursula Doyle\u2019s brother Noel Doyle. Christine lives in Toronto.\n\n==Death==\nJimmy O'Dea died at [[Dr Steevens' Hospital]], Dublin, aged 65, on January 6, 1965.<ref name=\"name1\"/>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Jimmy Boy]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[Cheer Boys Cheer]]'' (1939)\n* ''[[Let's Be Famous]]'' (1939)\n* ''[[The Rising of the Moon (film)|The Rising of the Moon]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Darby O'Gill and the Little People]]'' (1959)\n\n==Recordings==\nWith Harry O'Donovan:\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan nearly wins the Sweep\" E.3694 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan in London\" E.3895 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan at the telephone\" E.3663 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan at the talkies\" E.3764 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan at the racecourse\" E.3763 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan in the tram\" E.3764 Parlophone\n*\"The Irish Schoolmaster\" E.3634 Parlophone\n*\"Sixpence each way\" E.3634 Parlophone\n*\"Biddy Mulligan\" E 3817 Parlophone\n*\"Mrs. Mulligan, Smuggler\" \n*\"The Charladies' Ball\