{"title_page": "Salvatore Lupo", "text_new": "'''Salvatore Lupo''' ({{IPA-it|salva\u02c8to\u02d0re \u02c8lu\u02d0po}}; born 7 July 1951) is an Italian historian and author from [[Siena]], specializing in the [[Sicilian Mafia]].\n\nLupo is a professor of contemporary history at the [[University of Palermo]], previously professor of contemporary history at the [[University of Catania]]. He is the president of the Southern Institute of History and Social Sciences of Catania and deputy director of the quarterly magazine of the institute, ''Meridiana'',<ref>[http://digital.casalini.it/editori/default.asp?issn=03944115 Meridiana: rivista di storia e scienze sociali]</ref> of which he was one of the founders. He is a member of the editorial board of \"Storica\".\n\nHe is one of the most highly-rated mafia scholars in the Italian context, author of numerous publications on the crime phenomenon and contemporary history; he authored ''Quando la Mafia trov\u00f2 l'America'',<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2008/10/21/da-lucky-luciano-charles-gambino-boss-del.html|title= Da Lucky Luciano a Charles Gambino i boss del mare tra Sicilia e America|publisher= [[La Repubblica (quotidiano)|la Repubblica]]|date = 21 October 2008|language=Italian}}</ref> which, in 2009, won the Vitaliano Brancati literary prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.comune.zafferana-etnea.ct.it/Manifestazioni/Albo_doro_brancati.aspx|title= Albo d'oro premio Brancati|publisher= comune.zafferana-etnea.ct.it|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2015, in [[Rome]], he was invited to the hearing of the \"Parliamentary Commission of Inquiry into the Mafia phenomenon and other criminal associations, including foreign ones\", as part of the investigation into the relationship between the Mafia and politics in Sicily.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.camera.it/leg17/202|title=Audizione di marted\u00ec 01 dicembre 2015|publisher= Camera.it|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2015/12/01/lantimafia-indaga-sullantimafia-dopo-gli-scandali-audizioni-in-parlamento/2268634/|title= L\u2019Antimafia indaga sull\u2019antimafia: dopo gli scandali, audizioni in Parlamento|publisher= ilfattoquotidiano.it |language=Italian|date = 1 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url =http://palermo.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/10/21/news/salvatore_lupo_basta_con_gli_intoccabili_o_la_lotta_alla_mafia_perde_di_credibilita_-125583532/|title= Salvatore Lupo: \"Basta con gli intoccabili o la lotta alla mafia perde di credibilit\u00e0\"|publisher= [[La Repubblica (quotidiano)|la Repubblica]]|date = 21 October 2015|language=Italian }}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Blocco agrario e crisi in Sicilia tra le due guerre'', Napoli, Guida, 1981. {{ISBN|88-7042-082-5}}.\n* ''Agricoltura ricca nel sottosviluppo. Storia e mito della Sicilia agrumaria. (1860-1950)'', Catania, s. n., 1984.\n* ''La dimora di Demetra. Storia, tecnica e mito dell'agricoltura siciliana'', et Al., Palermo, Gelka, 1989. {{ISBN|88-7162-003-8}}.\n* ''Il giardino degli aranci. Il mondo degli agrumi nella storia del Mezzogiorno'', Venezia, Marsilio, 1990. {{ISBN|88-317-5310-X}}.\n* ''I proprietari terrieri nel Mezzogiorno'', in ''Storia dell'agricoltura italiana in et\u00e0 contemporanea'', II, ''Uomini e classi'', Venezia, Marsilio, 1990. {{ISBN|88-317-5381-9}}.\n* ''Storia della mafia. Dalle origini ai nostri giorni'', Roma, Donzelli, 1993. {{ISBN|88-7989-020-4}}; 1996. {{ISBN|88-7989-321-1}}; 2004. {{ISBN|88-7989-903-1}}.\n* ''Andreotti, la mafia, la storia d'Italia'', Roma, Donzelli, 1996. {{ISBN|88-7989-255-X}}.\n* ''Mafia, politica, storia d'Italia: a proposito del processo Andreotti'', in ''Antimafia'', Roma, Donzelli, 1996. {{ISBN|88-7989-269-X}}.\n* ''Il fascismo. La politica in un regime totalitario'', Roma, Donzelli, 2000. {{ISBN|88-7989-580-X}}.\n* ''Antifascismo, anticomunismo e anti-antifascismo nell'Italia repubblicana'', in AA.VV., ''Antifascismo e identit\u00e0 europea'', Roma, Carocci, 2004. {{ISBN|88-430-2934-7}}.\n* ''Partito e antipartito. Una storia politica della prima Repubblica, 1946-78'', Roma, Donzelli, 2004. {{ISBN|88-7989-769-1}}.\n* ''Che cos'\u00e8 la mafia. Sciascia e Andreotti, l'antimafia e la politica'', Roma, Donzelli, 2007. {{ISBN|88-6036-112-5}}.\n* ''From Palermo to America. L'iconografia commerciale dei limoni di Sicilia'', with [[Antonino Buttitta]] and [[Sergio Troisi]], Palermo, Sellerio, 2007. {{ISBN|9788876811586}}.\n* ''Quando la mafia trov\u00f2 l'America. Storia di un intreccio intercontinentale, 1888-2008'', Torino, Einaudi, 2008. {{ISBN|978-88-06-18598-5}}.\n* ''Potere criminale. Intervista sulla storia della mafia'', intervista a cura di [[Gaetano Savatteri]], Roma-Bari, Laterza, 2010. {{ISBN|978-88-420-9338-1}}.\n* ''Il passato del nostro presente. Il lungo Ottocento 1776-1913'', Roma-Bari, Laterza, 2010. {{ISBN|978-88-420-9399-2}}.\n* ''Il tenebroso sodalizio. Il primo rapporto di polizia sulla mafia siciliana'', postfazione di [[John Dickie (historian)|John Dickie]], Roma, XL, 2011. {{ISBN|978-88-6083-041-8}}.\n* ''L'unificazione italiana. Mezzogiorno, Rivoluzione, Guerra civile'', Roma, Donzelli, 2011. {{ISBN|978-88-6036-627-6}}.\n* ''Antipartiti. Il mito della nuova politica nella storia della Repubblica (prima, seconda e terza)'', Roma, Donzelli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-88-6036-856-0}}\n* ''Il fascismo: la politica in un regime totalitario'', Milano, Feltrinelli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-88-07-88294-4}}\n* ''La mafia non ha vinto. Il labirinto della trattativa'', with Giovanni Fiandaca, Roma-Bari, Laterza, 2014. {{ISBN|978-88-581-1046-1}}\n* ''La questione: come liberare la storia del Mezzogiorno dagli stereotipi'', Roma, Donzelli, 2015. {{ISBN|978-88-6843-232-4}}\n*La mafia. Centosessant'anni di Storia. Tra Sicilia e America, Roma, Donzelli, 2018. {{ISBN|978-88-6843-825-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lupo, Salvatore}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction writers about organized crime in Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Siena]]\n", "text_old": "'''Salvatore Lupo''' ({{IPA-it|salva\u02c8to\u02d0re \u02c8lu\u02d0po}}; born 7 July 1951) is an Italian historian and author from [[Siena]], specializing in the [[Sicilian Mafia]].\n\nLupo is a professor of contemporary history at the [[University of Palermo]], previously professor of contemporary history at the [[University of Catania]]. He is the president of the Southern Institute of History and Social Sciences of Catania and deputy director of the quarterly magazine of the institute, ''Meridiana'',<ref>[http://digital.casalini.it/editori/default.asp?issn=03944115 Meridiana: rivista di storia e scienze sociali]</ref> of which he was one of the founders. He is a member of the editorial board of \"Storica\".\n\nHe is one of the most highly-rated mafia scholars in the Italian context, author of numerous publications on the crime phenomenon and contemporary history; he authored ''Quando la Mafia trov\u00f2 l'America'',<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2008/10/21/da-lucky-luciano-charles-gambino-boss-del.html|title= Da Lucky Luciano a Charles Gambino i boss del mare tra Sicilia e America|publisher= [[La Repubblica (quotidiano)|la Repubblica]]|date = 21 October 2008|language=Italian}}</ref> which, in 2009, won the Vitaliano Brancati literary prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.comune.zafferana-etnea.ct.it/Manifestazioni/Albo_doro_brancati.aspx|title= Albo d'oro premio Brancati|publisher= comune.zafferana-etnea.ct.it|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2015, in [[Rome]], he was invited to the hearing of the \"Parliamentary Commission of Inquiry into the Mafia phenomenon and other criminal associations, including foreign ones\", as part of the investigation into the relationship between the Mafia and politics in Sicily.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.camera.it/leg17/202|title=Audizione di marted\u00ec 01 dicembre 2015|publisher= Camera.it|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2015/12/01/lantimafia-indaga-sullantimafia-dopo-gli-scandali-audizioni-in-parlamento/2268634/|title= L\u2019Antimafia indaga sull\u2019antimafia: dopo gli scandali, audizioni in Parlamento|publisher= ilfattoquotidiano.it |language=Italian|date = 1 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url =http://palermo.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/10/21/news/salvatore_lupo_basta_con_gli_intoccabili_o_la_lotta_alla_mafia_perde_di_credibilita_-125583532/|title= Salvatore Lupo: \"Basta con gli intoccabili o la lotta alla mafia perde di credibilit\u00e0\"|publisher= [[La Repubblica (quotidiano)|la Repubblica]]|date = 21 October 2015|language=Italian }}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Blocco agrario e crisi in Sicilia tra le due guerre'', Napoli, Guida, 1981. {{ISBN|88-7042-082-5}}.\n* ''Agricoltura ricca nel sottosviluppo. Storia e mito della Sicilia agrumaria. (1860-1950)'', Catania, s. n., 1984.\n* ''La dimora di Demetra. Storia, tecnica e mito dell'agricoltura siciliana'', et Al., Palermo, Gelka, 1989. {{ISBN|88-7162-003-8}}.\n* ''Il giardino degli aranci. Il mondo degli agrumi nella storia del Mezzogiorno'', Venezia, Marsilio, 1990. {{ISBN|88-317-5310-X}}.\n* ''I proprietari terrieri nel Mezzogiorno'', in ''Storia dell'agricoltura italiana in et\u00e0 contemporanea'', II, ''Uomini e classi'', Venezia, Marsilio, 1990. {{ISBN|88-317-5381-9}}.\n* ''Storia della mafia. Dalle origini ai nostri giorni'', Roma, Donzelli, 1993. {{ISBN|88-7989-020-4}}; 1996. {{ISBN|88-7989-321-1}}; 2004. {{ISBN|88-7989-903-1}}.\n* ''Andreotti, la mafia, la storia d'Italia'', Roma, Donzelli, 1996. {{ISBN|88-7989-255-X}}.\n* ''Mafia, politica, storia d'Italia: a proposito del processo Andreotti'', in ''Antimafia'', Roma, Donzelli, 1996. {{ISBN|88-7989-269-X}}.\n* ''Il fascismo. La politica in un regime totalitario'', Roma, Donzelli, 2000. {{ISBN|88-7989-580-X}}.\n* ''Antifascismo, anticomunismo e anti-antifascismo nell'Italia repubblicana'', in AA.VV., ''Antifascismo e identit\u00e0 europea'', Roma, Carocci, 2004. {{ISBN|88-430-2934-7}}.\n* ''Partito e antipartito. Una storia politica della prima Repubblica, 1946-78'', Roma, Donzelli, 2004. {{ISBN|88-7989-769-1}}.\n* ''Che cos'\u00e8 la mafia. Sciascia e Andreotti, l'antimafia e la politica'', Roma, Donzelli, 2007. {{ISBN|88-6036-112-5}}.\n* ''From Palermo to America. L'iconografia commerciale dei limoni di Sicilia'', with [[Antonino Buttitta]] and [[Sergio Troisi]], Palermo, Sellerio, 2007. {{ISBN|9788876811586}}.\n* ''Quando la mafia trov\u00f2 l'America. Storia di un intreccio intercontinentale, 1888-2008'', Torino, Einaudi, 2008. {{ISBN|978-88-06-18598-5}}.\n* ''Potere criminale. Intervista sulla storia della mafia'', intervista a cura di [[Gaetano Savatteri]], Roma-Bari, Laterza, 2010. {{ISBN|978-88-420-9338-1}}.\n* ''Il passato del nostro presente. Il lungo Ottocento 1776-1913'', Roma-Bari, Laterza, 2010. {{ISBN|978-88-420-9399-2}}.\n* ''Il tenebroso sodalizio. Il primo rapporto di polizia sulla mafia siciliana'', postfazione di [[John Dickie]], Roma, XL, 2011. {{ISBN|978-88-6083-041-8}}.\n* ''L'unificazione italiana. Mezzogiorno, Rivoluzione, Guerra civile'', Roma, Donzelli, 2011. {{ISBN|978-88-6036-627-6}}.\n* ''Antipartiti. Il mito della nuova politica nella storia della Repubblica (prima, seconda e terza)'', Roma, Donzelli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-88-6036-856-0}}\n* ''Il fascismo: la politica in un regime totalitario'', Milano, Feltrinelli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-88-07-88294-4}}\n* ''La mafia non ha vinto. Il labirinto della trattativa'', with Giovanni Fiandaca, Roma-Bari, Laterza, 2014. {{ISBN|978-88-581-1046-1}}\n* ''La questione: come liberare la storia del Mezzogiorno dagli stereotipi'', Roma, Donzelli, 2015. {{ISBN|978-88-6843-232-4}}\n*La mafia. Centosessant'anni di Storia. Tra Sicilia e America, Roma, Donzelli, 2018. {{ISBN|978-88-6843-825-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lupo, Salvatore}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction writers about organized crime in Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Siena]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Dickie(link changed toJohn Dickie (historian)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salvatore_Lupo"}
{"title_page": "Sweet Caroline", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|1969 single by Neil Diamond}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sweet Caroline\n| cover      = Sweet Caroline cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Dig In\n| released   = 28 May 1969\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 3:21\n| label      = [[Uni Records|Uni]]/[[MCA Records|MCA]]\n| writer     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Tommy Cogbill]]|[[Neil Diamond]]|[[Tom Catalano]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Brother Love's Traveling Salvation Show (song)|Brother Love's Traveling Salvation Show]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Holly Holy]]\n| next_year  = 1969\n}}\n\n\"'''Sweet Caroline'''\" is a song written and performed by American singer [[Neil Diamond]] and released in May 1969<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Neil-Diamond-Sweet-Caroline-Good-Times-Never-Seemed-So-Good/release/1325064|last=Discogs|title=Neil Diamond \u2013 Sweet Caroline (Good Times Never Seemed So Good)|accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> as a [[single (song)|single]] with the title \"'''Sweet Caroline (Good Times Never Seemed So Good)'''\". It was arranged by [[Charles Calello]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlescalello.com/Hit_Records.htm|first=Charles|last=Calello|title=Calello's Billboard Magazine Top 100|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> and recorded at [[American Sound Studio]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].\n\n==Inspiration==\n\nIn a 2007 interview, Diamond stated the inspiration for his song was [[John F. Kennedy]]'s daughter, [[Caroline Kennedy|Caroline]], who was eleven years old at the time it was released.<ref name = \"guard\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/usa/story/0,,2214419,00.html | title = Neil Diamond reveals secret of Sweet Caroline| accessdate= June 13, 2015| newspaper = [[The Guardian]] |first = Dan | last = Glaister | location = London | date = November 21, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2007/11/21/sweet_caroline_revealed/ |title= 'Sweet Caroline' revealed |accessdate=March 15, 2008|newspaper= [[The Boston Globe]]| first1= Carol | last1= Beggy | first2 = Mark | last2 = Shanahan | date = November 21, 2007}}</ref> Diamond sang the song to her at her 50th birthday celebration in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/20/AR2007112000598_pf.html | title = Diamond Reveals `Caroline' Inspiration |agency=Associated Press |date=November 20, 2007|first=Sandy|last= Cohen |newspaper=Washington Post |accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref> On December 21, 2011, in an interview on CBS's ''[[The Early Show]]'', Diamond said that a magazine cover photo of Caroline Kennedy as a young child on a horse<ref>https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2007/11/photo_hulton_archivegetty_imag.html</ref> with her parents created an image in his mind, and the rest of the song came together about five years after seeing the picture.<ref name=CNN2017>{{cite news|last=Respers |first=Lisa |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/20/showbiz/music/neil-diamond-sweet-caroline/ |title=Neil Diamond reveals story behind 'Sweet Caroline' |work=CNN |date=October 20, 2014 |accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> However, in 2014 Diamond said the song was about his then-wife Marcia, but he needed a three-syllable name to fit the melody.<ref name=CNN2017/> The song has proven to be enduringly popular and, as of November 2014, has sold over two million [[music download|digital downloads]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6327774/revisionist-history-part-5-bon-jovis-prayer-answered-caroline-is |title=Revisionist History, Part 5: Bon Jovi's 'Prayer' Answered, 'Caroline' Is Sweeter Than 'Sugar' |last=Appel |first=Rich |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=November 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\n\nThe song reached No. 4 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart the week ending August 16, 1969,<ref>[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]], [https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1969-08-16 Hot 100], August 16, 1969</ref> and was certified [[Music recording sales certification|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] on August 18, 1969, for sales of one million singles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=&ti=sweet+caroline&lab=&genre=&format=&date_option=release&from=&to=&award=&type=&category=&adv=SEARCH#search_section |title=Gold & Platinum |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=www.riaa.com |publisher=RIAA |access-date=January 8, 2018 }}</ref> \"Sweet Caroline\" was also the first of fifty-eight entries on the US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] chart, peaking at #3.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961-2001|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2002 |publisher=Record Research |page=78}}</ref>\n\nIn the autumn of 1969, Diamond performed \"Sweet Caroline\" on several television shows. It later reached No. 8 on the UK singles chart in 1971.\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report|KMR]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6010&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6010.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6010|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|Canada Adult Contemporary (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6011&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6011.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6011|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(D).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|4|artist=Neil Diamond  |accessdate=June 15, 2018}}\n|-\n|US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Neil-Diamond/chart-history/adult-contemporary|title=Neil Diamond Chart History (Easy Listening)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19690830.html|title=Cash Box Top 100 8/30/69|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=October 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022085311/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19690830.html|archive-date=October 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany|37|artist=Neil Diamond|song=Sweet Caroline}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|9|song=Sweet Caroline|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|16|artist=Neil Diamond|song=Sweet Caroline}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|8|artist=Neil Diamond}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6104&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6104.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6104|title=RPM Top Singles of 1969|accessdate=24 December 2017|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|website=[[Library and Archives Canada]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|37\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1969.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1969/Top 100 Songs of 1969|website=www.musicoutfitters.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1969YESP.html|title=Cash Box YE Pop Singles - 1969|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=October 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125055422/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1969YESP.html|archive-date=January 25, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|26\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Alternate versions==\nThere are three distinct mixes of this song. In the original mono 45 mix, the orchestra and [[glockenspiel]] are more prominent than in the stereo version on the ''[[Brother Love's Travelling Salvation Show]]'' LP. The third version was a remix found only on the initial CD release of Diamond's ''[[His 12 Greatest Hits]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.netcom.com/~zmoq/pages/ndalbum4.htm |title=Neil Diamond Album Overview Part 4: 1981-2003 The Compilation-Mania Years |access-date=June 13, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030060740/http://home.netcom.com/~zmoq/pages/ndalbum4.htm |archive-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This version has the orchestra mixed down and has the background vocals mixed up. It has a longer fade as well. A live version of the song is on his ''[[Hot August Night]]'' LP.\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Diamond changed some of the lyrics to \"Hands ... washing hands ... don't touch me ... I won't touch you.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.journalnow.com/news/national/if-you-dont-laugh-you-cry-coping-with-virus-through-humor/article_2be1bdb2-2aab-51fd-b4d6-0b841910365e.html|title=If you don't laugh, you cry: Coping with virus through humor|last=Kole|first=William J.|work=[[Winston-Salem Journal]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Use at sporting events==\n===United States===\nThe song has been played at [[Fenway Park]], home of [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[Boston Red Sox]], since at least 1997,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://www.mlb.com/news/fenway-parks-anthem-started-innocuously/c-45075964 | title = Fenway Park's anthem started innocuously | first = Ian | last = Browne | website = MLB.com | date = April 17, 2013 | accessdate = April 20, 2016 }}</ref> and in the middle of the eighth inning at every game since 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/articles/2005/05/29/another_mystery_of_the_diamond_explained_at_last/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Another mystery of the Diamond, explained at last | date=May 29, 2005 | first1=Stephanie | last1=Vosk}}</ref> On opening night of the 2010 season at Fenway Park, the song was performed live by Diamond himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nesn.com/2010/04/reports-neil-diamond-to-sing-sweet-caroline-live-at-fenway-park/|title=Neil Diamond Sings 'Sweet Caroline' Live at Fenway Park|first=Adam|last=Hirschfield|date=April 4, 2010|accessdate=January 6, 2019|work=NESN}}</ref> \"Sweet Caroline\" was played at [[Penn State Nittany Lions football]] games at [[Beaver Stadium]] until August 2012, when it was supposedly halted due to the [[Penn State child sex abuse scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark |first=Lauren |url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/blog/2012/08/27/penn-state-reminds-sweet-caroline-kind-creepy/ |title=Penn State Kills 'Sweet Caroline' |work=Boston Magazine |date=2012-08-27 |accessdate=2016-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.blogs.cnn.com/2012/08/28/no-sweet-caroline-at-penn-state-games-no-public-allowed-in-most-athletic-facilities/ |title=No 'Sweet Caroline' at Penn State games, no public allowed in most athletic facilities \u2013 This Just In |publisher=CNN.com Blogs |date= |accessdate=2016-10-02}}</ref> Performances at Beaver Stadium resumed in September 2013, however.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horne |first=Kevin |url=https://onwardstate.com/2013/09/23/sweet-caroline-returns-to-beaver-stadium/ |title=Sweet Caroline Returns to Beaver Stadium |publisher=Onward State |date=2013-09-23 |accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> The [[Iowa State Cyclones]] have used \"Sweet Caroline\" as a football victory song since 2006.<ref name=\"Des Moines Register\">{{cite news|last1=Leimkuehler|first1=Matthew|title=How Neil Diamond\u2019s 'Sweet Caroline' became Iowa State\u2019s inescapable celebration song|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/09/07/sweet-caroline-iowa-state-cyclones-athletics-football-basketball-neil-diamond-cyhawk-boston-redsox/1211156002/|work=Des Moines Register}}</ref>\n\n====Boston Marathon====\nSeveral days after the [[Boston Marathon bombing]] in April 2013, Neil Diamond led the crowd at Fenway Park in a rendition of the song.<ref name=\"cbs2013\">{{cite news |last1=Perry |first1=Dayn |title=Neil Diamond sang at Fenway . . . uninvited |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/neil-diamond-sang-at-fenway----uninvited/ |accessdate=8 September 2019 |publisher=CBS Sports |date=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nSales of the song surged nearly 600 percent in the week after the bombings, to 19,000 copies, up from 2,800 the week before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/neil-diamond-donate-sweet-caroline-446537|title=Neil Diamond to Donate 'Sweet Caroline' Royalties to Boston Charity|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 25, 2013|accessdate=April 25, 2013}}</ref> Diamond said that he would donate his royalties from those sales  to the One Fund Boston charity to help the people affected by the bombings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/25/neil-diamond-to-donate-sweet-caroline-royalties-to-boston-bombing-charity/|title=Neil Diamond to Donate 'Sweet Caroline' Royalties to Boston Bombing Charity|work=The New York Times|date=April 25, 2013|accessdate=April 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nThe song is popular in Britain and has been adopted by many football clubs including [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].\n\nIt is also used by the [[Castleford Tigers]] rugby league team upon victory at their home ground, The Jungle, over a rival club.\n\n===Mixed Martial Arts===\n[[UFC]] welterweight fighter [[Darren Till]] has adopted the song as his entrance music beginning at [[UFC Fight Night: Thompson vs. Till]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joe.co.uk/sport/darren-till-explains-choice-of-walkout-music-in-deafening-echo-arena-180993/|title=DARREN TILL EXPLAINS CHOICE OF WALKOUT MUSIC IN DEAFENING ECHO ARENA}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Neil Diamond]] - vocals, acoustic guitar\n*[[Charles Calello]] - string, horn and vocal arrangements\n*[[The Memphis Boys]] - other instrumentation\n**[[Gene Chrisman]] - drums\n**[[Tommy Cogbill]] - bass guitar\n**[[Bobby Emmons]] - keyboards   \n**[[Reggie Young]] - electric guitar\n\n==DJ \u00d6tzi versions==\n[[DJ \u00d6tzi]], an Austrian entertainer and singer released it in 2009, peaking at number 19 on the German Singles Chart and number 18 on the Austrian charts.<ref>[http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=DJ+%D6tzi&titel=Sweet+Caroline&cat=s Austriancharts.at: DJ \u00d6TZI - \"Sweet Caroline\"]</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2019, \"Sweet Caroline\" was selected by the [[Library of Congress]] for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]] for being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Andrews |first=Travis M. |date=March 20, 2019 |title=Jay-Z, a speech by Sen. Robert F. Kennedy and 'Schoolhouse Rock!' among recordings deemed classics by Library of Congress |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/jay-z-a-speech-by-sen-robert-f-kennedy-and-schoolhouse-rock-among-recordings-deemed-classics-by-library-of-congress/2019/03/19/f7eb08ea-4a58-11e9-9663-00ac73f49662_story.html?|work=The Washington Post|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://youtube.com/watch?v=GmK5_lnQUbE Official audio]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|neil-diamond|sweet-caroline}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Neil Diamond singles}}\n{{Boston Red Sox}}\n{{Carolina Panthers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sweet Caroline}}\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Neil Diamond]]\n[[Category:Baseball songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Neil Diamond songs]]\n[[Category:Checkmates, Ltd. songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Womack songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Chips Moman]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Football songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox]]\n[[Category:Carolina Panthers]]\n[[Category:Uni Records singles]]\n[[Category:MCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|1969 single by Neil Diamond}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sweet Caroline\n| cover      = Sweet Caroline cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Dig In\n| released   = 28 May 1969\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 3:21\n| label      = [[Uni Records|Uni]]/[[MCA Records|MCA]]\n| writer     = [[Neil Diamond]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Tommy Cogbill]]|[[Neil Diamond]]|[[Tom Catalano]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Brother Love's Traveling Salvation Show (song)|Brother Love's Traveling Salvation Show]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Holly Holy]]\n| next_year  = 1969\n}}\n\n\"'''Sweet Caroline'''\" is a song written and performed by American singer [[Neil Diamond]] and released in May 1969<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Neil-Diamond-Sweet-Caroline-Good-Times-Never-Seemed-So-Good/release/1325064|last=Discogs|title=Neil Diamond \u2013 Sweet Caroline (Good Times Never Seemed So Good)|accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> as a [[single (song)|single]] with the title \"'''Sweet Caroline (Good Times Never Seemed So Good)'''\". It was arranged by [[Charles Calello]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlescalello.com/Hit_Records.htm|first=Charles|last=Calello|title=Calello's Billboard Magazine Top 100|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> and recorded at [[American Sound Studio]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].\n\n==Inspiration==\n\nIn a 2007 interview, Diamond stated the inspiration for his song was [[John F. Kennedy]]'s daughter, [[Caroline Kennedy|Caroline]], who was eleven years old at the time it was released.<ref name = \"guard\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/usa/story/0,,2214419,00.html | title = Neil Diamond reveals secret of Sweet Caroline| accessdate= June 13, 2015| newspaper = [[The Guardian]] |first = Dan | last = Glaister | location = London | date = November 21, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2007/11/21/sweet_caroline_revealed/ |title= 'Sweet Caroline' revealed |accessdate=March 15, 2008|newspaper= [[The Boston Globe]]| first1= Carol | last1= Beggy | first2 = Mark | last2 = Shanahan | date = November 21, 2007}}</ref> Diamond sang the song to her at her 50th birthday celebration in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/20/AR2007112000598_pf.html | title = Diamond Reveals `Caroline' Inspiration |agency=Associated Press |date=November 20, 2007|first=Sandy|last= Cohen |newspaper=Washington Post |accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref> On December 21, 2011, in an interview on CBS's ''[[The Early Show]]'', Diamond said that a magazine cover photo of Caroline Kennedy as a young child on a horse<ref>https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2007/11/photo_hulton_archivegetty_imag.html</ref> with her parents created an image in his mind, and the rest of the song came together about five years after seeing the picture.<ref name=CNN2017>{{cite news|last=Respers |first=Lisa |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/20/showbiz/music/neil-diamond-sweet-caroline/ |title=Neil Diamond reveals story behind 'Sweet Caroline' |work=CNN |date=October 20, 2014 |accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> However, in 2014 Diamond said the song was about his then-wife Marcia, but he needed a three-syllable name to fit the melody.<ref name=CNN2017/> The song has proven to be enduringly popular and, as of November 2014, has sold over two million [[music download|digital downloads]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6327774/revisionist-history-part-5-bon-jovis-prayer-answered-caroline-is |title=Revisionist History, Part 5: Bon Jovi's 'Prayer' Answered, 'Caroline' Is Sweeter Than 'Sugar' |last=Appel |first=Rich |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=November 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\n\nThe song reached No. 4 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart the week ending August 16, 1969,<ref>[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]], [https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1969-08-16 Hot 100], August 16, 1969</ref> and was certified [[Music recording sales certification|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] on August 18, 1969, for sales of one million singles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=&ti=sweet+caroline&lab=&genre=&format=&date_option=release&from=&to=&award=&type=&category=&adv=SEARCH#search_section |title=Gold & Platinum |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=www.riaa.com |publisher=RIAA |access-date=January 8, 2018 }}</ref> \"Sweet Caroline\" was also the first of fifty-eight entries on the US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] chart, peaking at #3.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961-2001|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2002 |publisher=Record Research |page=78}}</ref>\n\nIn the autumn of 1969, Diamond performed \"Sweet Caroline\" on several television shows. It later reached No. 8 on the UK singles chart in 1971.\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report|KMR]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6010&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6010.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6010|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|Canada Adult Contemporary (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6011&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6011.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6011|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(D).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|4|artist=Neil Diamond  |accessdate=June 15, 2018}}\n|-\n|US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Neil-Diamond/chart-history/adult-contemporary|title=Neil Diamond Chart History (Easy Listening)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19690830.html|title=Cash Box Top 100 8/30/69|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=October 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022085311/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19690830.html|archive-date=October 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany|37|artist=Neil Diamond|song=Sweet Caroline}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|9|song=Sweet Caroline|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|16|artist=Neil Diamond|song=Sweet Caroline}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|8|artist=Neil Diamond}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6104&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6104.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6104|title=RPM Top Singles of 1969|accessdate=24 December 2017|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|website=[[Library and Archives Canada]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|37\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1969.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1969/Top 100 Songs of 1969|website=www.musicoutfitters.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1969YESP.html|title=Cash Box YE Pop Singles - 1969|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=October 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125055422/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1969YESP.html|archive-date=January 25, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|26\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Alternate versions==\nThere are three distinct mixes of this song. In the original mono 45 mix, the orchestra and [[glockenspiel]] are more prominent than in the stereo version on the ''[[Brother Love's Travelling Salvation Show]]'' LP. The third version was a remix found only on the initial CD release of Diamond's ''[[His 12 Greatest Hits]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.netcom.com/~zmoq/pages/ndalbum4.htm |title=Neil Diamond Album Overview Part 4: 1981-2003 The Compilation-Mania Years |access-date=June 13, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030060740/http://home.netcom.com/~zmoq/pages/ndalbum4.htm |archive-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This version has the orchestra mixed down and has the background vocals mixed up. It has a longer fade as well. A live version of the song is on his ''[[Hot August Night]]'' LP.\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Diamond changed some of the lyrics to \"Hands ... washing hands ... don't touch me ... I won't touch you.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.journalnow.com/news/national/if-you-dont-laugh-you-cry-coping-with-virus-through-humor/article_2be1bdb2-2aab-51fd-b4d6-0b841910365e.html|title=If you don't laugh, you cry: Coping with virus through humor|last=Kole|first=William J.|work=[[Winston-Salem Journal]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Use at sporting events==\n===United States===\nThe song has been played at [[Fenway Park]], home of [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[Boston Red Sox]], since at least 1997,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://www.mlb.com/news/fenway-parks-anthem-started-innocuously/c-45075964 | title = Fenway Park's anthem started innocuously | first = Ian | last = Browne | website = MLB.com | date = April 17, 2013 | accessdate = April 20, 2016 }}</ref> and in the middle of the eighth inning at every game since 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/articles/2005/05/29/another_mystery_of_the_diamond_explained_at_last/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Another mystery of the Diamond, explained at last | date=May 29, 2005 | first1=Stephanie | last1=Vosk}}</ref> On opening night of the 2010 season at Fenway Park, the song was performed live by Diamond himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nesn.com/2010/04/reports-neil-diamond-to-sing-sweet-caroline-live-at-fenway-park/|title=Neil Diamond Sings 'Sweet Caroline' Live at Fenway Park|first=Adam|last=Hirschfield|date=April 4, 2010|accessdate=January 6, 2019|work=NESN}}</ref> \"Sweet Caroline\" was played at [[Penn State Nittany Lions football]] games at [[Beaver Stadium]] until August 2012, when it was supposedly halted due to the [[Penn State child sex abuse scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark |first=Lauren |url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/blog/2012/08/27/penn-state-reminds-sweet-caroline-kind-creepy/ |title=Penn State Kills 'Sweet Caroline' |work=Boston Magazine |date=2012-08-27 |accessdate=2016-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.blogs.cnn.com/2012/08/28/no-sweet-caroline-at-penn-state-games-no-public-allowed-in-most-athletic-facilities/ |title=No 'Sweet Caroline' at Penn State games, no public allowed in most athletic facilities \u2013 This Just In |publisher=CNN.com Blogs |date= |accessdate=2016-10-02}}</ref> Performances at Beaver Stadium resumed in September 2013, however.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horne |first=Kevin |url=https://onwardstate.com/2013/09/23/sweet-caroline-returns-to-beaver-stadium/ |title=Sweet Caroline Returns to Beaver Stadium |publisher=Onward State |date=2013-09-23 |accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> The [[Iowa State Cyclones]] have used \"Sweet Caroline\" as a football victory song since 2006.<ref name=\"Des Moines Register\">{{cite news|last1=Leimkuehler|first1=Matthew|title=How Neil Diamond\u2019s 'Sweet Caroline' became Iowa State\u2019s inescapable celebration song|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/09/07/sweet-caroline-iowa-state-cyclones-athletics-football-basketball-neil-diamond-cyhawk-boston-redsox/1211156002/|work=Des Moines Register}}</ref>\n\n====Boston Marathon====\nSeveral days after the [[Boston Marathon bombing]] in April 2013, Neil Diamond led the crowd at Fenway Park in a rendition of the song.<ref name=\"cbs2013\">{{cite news |last1=Perry |first1=Dayn |title=Neil Diamond sang at Fenway . . . uninvited |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/neil-diamond-sang-at-fenway----uninvited/ |accessdate=8 September 2019 |publisher=CBS Sports |date=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nSales of the song surged nearly 600 percent in the week after the bombings, to 19,000 copies, up from 2,800 the week before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/neil-diamond-donate-sweet-caroline-446537|title=Neil Diamond to Donate 'Sweet Caroline' Royalties to Boston Charity|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 25, 2013|accessdate=April 25, 2013}}</ref> Diamond said that he would donate his royalties from those sales  to the One Fund Boston charity to help the people affected by the bombings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/25/neil-diamond-to-donate-sweet-caroline-royalties-to-boston-bombing-charity/|title=Neil Diamond to Donate 'Sweet Caroline' Royalties to Boston Bombing Charity|work=The New York Times|date=April 25, 2013|accessdate=April 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nThe song is popular in Britain and has been adopted by many football clubs including [[Oxford United]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal F.C]].\n\nIt is also used by the [[Castleford Tigers]] rugby league team upon victory at their home ground, The Jungle, over a rival club.\n\n===Mixed Martial Arts===\n[[UFC]] welterweight fighter [[Darren Till]] has adopted the song as his entrance music beginning at [[UFC Fight Night: Thompson vs. Till]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joe.co.uk/sport/darren-till-explains-choice-of-walkout-music-in-deafening-echo-arena-180993/|title=DARREN TILL EXPLAINS CHOICE OF WALKOUT MUSIC IN DEAFENING ECHO ARENA}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Neil Diamond]] - vocals, acoustic guitar\n*[[Charles Calello]] - string, horn and vocal arrangements\n*[[The Memphis Boys]] - other instrumentation\n**[[Gene Chrisman]] - drums\n**[[Tommy Cogbill]] - bass guitar\n**[[Bobby Emmons]] - keyboards   \n**[[Reggie Young]] - electric guitar\n\n==DJ \u00d6tzi versions==\n[[DJ \u00d6tzi]], an Austrian entertainer and singer released it in 2009, peaking at number 19 on the German Singles Chart and number 18 on the Austrian charts.<ref>[http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=DJ+%D6tzi&titel=Sweet+Caroline&cat=s Austriancharts.at: DJ \u00d6TZI - \"Sweet Caroline\"]</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2019, \"Sweet Caroline\" was selected by the [[Library of Congress]] for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]] for being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Andrews |first=Travis M. |date=March 20, 2019 |title=Jay-Z, a speech by Sen. Robert F. Kennedy and 'Schoolhouse Rock!' among recordings deemed classics by Library of Congress |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/jay-z-a-speech-by-sen-robert-f-kennedy-and-schoolhouse-rock-among-recordings-deemed-classics-by-library-of-congress/2019/03/19/f7eb08ea-4a58-11e9-9663-00ac73f49662_story.html?|work=The Washington Post|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://youtube.com/watch?v=GmK5_lnQUbE Official audio]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|neil-diamond|sweet-caroline}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Neil Diamond singles}}\n{{Boston Red Sox}}\n{{Carolina Panthers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sweet Caroline}}\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Neil Diamond]]\n[[Category:Baseball songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Neil Diamond songs]]\n[[Category:Checkmates, Ltd. songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Womack songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Chips Moman]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Football songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox]]\n[[Category:Carolina Panthers]]\n[[Category:Uni Records singles]]\n[[Category:MCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n", "name_user": "Once in a Lifetime", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited Kingdom:format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweet_Caroline"}
{"title_page": "Sacha Lord", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sacha Lord\n| image         = Photo_of_Sacha_Lord,_November_2019.jpg\n| alt           = Sacha Lord in November 2019\n| caption       = Sacha Lord in November 2019\n| birth_name    = Sacha John Edward Lord\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1972|01|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Manchester]], United Kingdom\n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = {{Hlist|Music entrepreneur|Adviser}}\n| known_for     = {{Unbulleted list|Co-founder of [[The Warehouse Project]]|Co-founder of [[Parklife (festival)]]|Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]]}}\n| website = {{URL|https://parklife.uk.com|Parklife Festival}}\n}}\n\n'''Sacha John Edward Lord''' (born 26th January 1972) is an English entrepreneur and co-creator of the [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife festival]] and [[The Warehouse Project]]. He is also the Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n== Early life ==\n\nLord was born in [[Altrincham]], Greater Manchester, and grew up in the town. His father was a textile merchant, and his mother an interior designer. Lord was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]], leaving at aged 18 having gained two Us and an E at A-Level.  After leaving school, Lord went on to work at a clothes shop in [[Altrincham]], and later started a market stall at [[Liverpool]] market, selling leather jackets. After quitting his market job, Lord quickly found himself involved in the rave-influenced music scene, and spent most of his time listening to [[The Stone Roses]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[The Smiths]] and [[David Bowie|Bowie]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|publisher=Square Mile}}</ref>\n\n== The Warehouse Project ==\n\nInspired by the success of the events, Lord launched [[the Warehouse Project]], a series of rave events running annually from September to 1 January, in 2006 with Co-Founder Sam Kandel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enforbusiness.com/interview/five-minutes-sacha-lord-marchionne-and-sam-kandel-founders-warehouse-project|title=Five minutes with... Sacha Lord-Marchionne and Sam Kandel, founders of the Warehouse Project|website=EN For Business|accessdate=1 October 2019}}}</ref>\n\nIt began operations in the disused [[Strangeways Brewery|Boddingtons Brewery]] in [[Strangeways]], and then moved into a space under [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly station]], on Store Street, which previously served as an air raid shelter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djmag.com/news/detail/921|title=The Warehouse Project|website=djmag.com|publisher=DJ Mag}}</ref>\n\nThe opening night of The Warehouse Project was described by Lord as a nightmare due to its location next to the prison, and he later revealed the Governor of [[HM Prison Manchester]] had called to say it was disturbing inmates.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project went onto feature some of the most in-demand names in international house and techno music, including [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[The Chemical Brothers]] and [[Calvin Harris]] - whose appearance, Lord later went onto reveal, was a favour for an A&R at Sony. Lord revealed he put Harris ( an unknown DJ at the time) on the 21.30 slot, despite doors only opening at 22.00.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project attracted 100,000 people in its first year and has continued to sell out annually.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/sacha-lord-warehouse-project-founder-appointed-manchesters-night-time-economy-adviser-future-24-hour-clubbing-2366958#CPOiVsbVBBUvryY5.99|title=Sacha Lord: the Warehouse Project founder and Manchester\u2019s Night Time Economy Adviser on the future of the city\u2019s club scene|website=NME|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Lord and Kandel moved The Warehouse Project to Depot at the former [[Manchester Mayfield railway station]] - a move which saw it become the biggest club night in the UK with a 10,000 person capacity. The move also put it on a par with the current Guinness Book of World Records holder of the largest nightclub in the world, [[Privilege Ibiza|Privilege]] in Ibiza, which can also hold 10,000 revellers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pretty52.com/news/music-the-worlds-biggest-nightclub-is-opening-in-manchester-20190718|title=The UK's Biggest Club Night With 10,000 Capacity Is Opening In Manchester|website=pretty52.com|publisher=Pretty52}}</ref>\n\n== Parklife Festival ==\n\nLord co-created [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife Festival]] in 2010, to celebrate artists across indie, house and techno music.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> It has hosted some of the biggest names in music, including [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Liam Gallagher]] and [[Skepta]]. \n\nThe weekend festival, which moved from Platt Fields<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/parklife-festival-too-big-platt-689660|title=Festival \u2018too big\u2019 for Platt Fields|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> to Heaton Park, Manchester in 2012,<ref>http://parklifetickets.co.uk/history-of-parklife-festival/</ref> attracts 80,000 visitors each year.\n\nThe Festival employs over 4,500 people over the weekend and brings more than \u00a310million into the local economy. Each year, it raises over \u00a3100k for the Parklife Community Foundation, that is distributed to help local causes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ilovemanchester.com/how-parklife-grew-from-a-one-day-event-in-a-field-to-a-weekend-festival-bringing-in-160000-people/|title=How Parklife grew from a one day event in a field to a weekend festival bringing in 160,000 people|website=I Love MCR|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Hide Out Festival ==\n\nLord was one of the creators of Croatia\u2019s [[Hideout Festival]], a five-day alternative music extravaganza held on the island of [[Pag (island)|Pag]], Croatia, in 2011. It has sold out every single year since its conception.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political Activity ==\n\nIn 2018, Mayor of Greater Manchester, [[Andy Burnham]], appointed Lord as Greater Manchester\u2019s first Night Time Economy Adviser, following in the footsteps of [[Amy Lam\u00e9]], who was appointed by [[Mayor of London|London Mayor]] [[Sadiq Khan]] in 2016 to be the first London night czar.\n\nUnlike Lam\u00e9, who competed with 180 people for the \u00a335,000-a-year part-time role, Lord is not paid and any income created from the role has been donated directly to charity; and did not apply for the post, although it has been established that he lobbied Burnham on the importance of nightlife before the Labour politician won the inaugural mayoral elections in May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=theguardian.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe role acts to advise Burnham and the [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority]] (GMCA) on all issues relating to the night-time economy, providing a voice for workers, operators and the industry as a whole.\n\nLord has since announced a raft of recommendations to improve safety, transport and cultural diversity in the region,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.morningadvertiser.co.uk/Article/2019/08/15/Manchester-night-czar-Sacha-Lord-and-mayor-Andy-Burnham-unveil-city-blueprint|title=Manchester night czar: night time venues can revive high street|website=morningadvertiser.co.uk|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> including the introduction of later opening hours for greater accessibility and the development of night-time transport links to better serve under-represented communities on the outskirts of the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/its-time-247-transport-system-16667993|title=Mayor's night tsar calls for Greater Manchester to have 24/7 transport system|first=Jennifer|last=Williams|date=July 30, 2019|website=men}}</ref>\n\nLord has also advocated for a fair wage policy for nighttime hospitality staff, including full transparency\u00a0tipping for bar and restaurant workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/8xbvzv/can-manchesters-new-night-czar-make-tipping-fair|title=Can Manchester\u2019s New Night Czar Make Tipping Fair?|website=Vice|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Lord appeared on BBC Question Time, alongside Conservative Party chairman James Cleverly, Labour\u2019s Sarah Jones, National Farmers\u2019 Union (NFU) president Minette Batters and stand-up comedian Geoff Norcott. The transmission was the last episode to be broadcast before Britain left the European Union on 31 January 2020. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000dv70/question-time-2019-30012020|title=BBC Question Time 30 01 2020|website=BBC|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nIn 2006, [[The Warehouse Project]] was found solely responsible for an increase in drug-taking in [[HM Prison Manchester|Strangeways Prison]], leading to the event being scrutinised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aah-magazine.co.uk/2018/sacha-lord-marchionne-a-glance-at-the-man-behind-warehouse-project-parklife-and-a-key-figure-in-manchesters-nightlife|title=SACHA LORD-MARCHIONNE: A GLANCE AT THE MAN BEHIND WAREHOUSE PROJECT, PARKLIFE AND A KEY FIGURE IN MANCHESTER\u2019S NIGHTLIFE|website=Aah Magazine|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> This was because the venue was right next door and the prisoners could hear the music.\n\nIn 2012, Souvik Pal, aged 18, was ejected from a Warehouse Project event on suspicion of drug use; his body was found in nearby Bridgewater Canal 22 days later.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=Square Mile|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> In 2013, Nick Bonnie, 30, collapsed at the Warehouse Project after taking almost 15 times the standard recreational dose of [[MDMA]], and subsequently died in hospital.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=The Guardian|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLord was not directly responsible for either incident,<ref name=\"auto\"/> however, implemented drug-testing across events following the tragedies.\n\nIn 2018, Lord called for all UK clubs and festivals to have drug-testing laboratories on site,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and implemented the testing at The Warehouse Festival, which involves confiscated drugs being tested on site, and allowing alerts to be put out warning attendees of what the drugs actually are.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n== Charitable Work ==\n\nSacha Lord is patron of the Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity (charity reg number 1151518).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joshwilson.org.uk/|title=Home &#124; The Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity}}</ref>\n\nLord is also an avid campaigner on the role of mental health services for those working in the night time economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/parklife-breaks-me-sacha-lord-16039779|title='Parklife breaks me' - Sacha Lord on why night time workers need to talk about mental health|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the global Coronavirus pandemic in 2020, Lord founded the UnitedWeStream Manchester campaign<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/united-stream-goes-live-tonight-18032330|title='United We Stream goes live tonight as even more acts announced - including Hacienda night|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>, a livestream gig website which sought to raise money for the night time economy and charities in Greater Manchester through a relief fund on the website. A number of artists performed on the live stream website, including [[Roger Sanchez]] and [[Paul Oakenfold]].\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lord, Sacha}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music festival founders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sacha Lord\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Sacha John Edward Lord\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1972|01|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Manchester]], United Kingdom\n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = {{Hlist|Music entrepreneur|Adviser}}\n| known_for     = {{Unbulleted list|Co-founder of [[The Warehouse Project]]|Co-founder of [[Parklife (festival)]]|Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]]}}\n| website = {{URL|https://parklife.uk.com|Parklife Festival}}\n}}\n\n'''Sacha John Edward Lord''' (born 26th January 1972) is an English entrepreneur and co-creator of the [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife festival]] and [[The Warehouse Project]]. He is also the Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n== Early life ==\n\nLord was born in [[Altrincham]], Greater Manchester, and grew up in the town. His father was a textile merchant, and his mother an interior designer. Lord was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]], leaving at aged 18 having gained two Us and an E at A-Level.  After leaving school, Lord went on to work at a clothes shop in [[Altrincham]], and later started a market stall at [[Liverpool]] market, selling leather jackets. After quitting his market job, Lord quickly found himself involved in the rave-influenced music scene, and spent most of his time listening to [[The Stone Roses]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[The Smiths]] and [[David Bowie|Bowie]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|publisher=Square Mile}}</ref>\n\n== The Warehouse Project ==\n\nInspired by the success of the events, Lord launched [[the Warehouse Project]], a series of rave events running annually from September to 1 January, in 2006 with Co-Founder Sam Kandel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enforbusiness.com/interview/five-minutes-sacha-lord-marchionne-and-sam-kandel-founders-warehouse-project|title=Five minutes with... Sacha Lord-Marchionne and Sam Kandel, founders of the Warehouse Project|website=EN For Business|accessdate=1 October 2019}}}</ref>\n\nIt began operations in the disused [[Strangeways Brewery|Boddingtons Brewery]] in [[Strangeways]], and then moved into a space under [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly station]], on Store Street, which previously served as an air raid shelter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djmag.com/news/detail/921|title=The Warehouse Project|website=djmag.com|publisher=DJ Mag}}</ref>\n\nThe opening night of The Warehouse Project was described by Lord as a nightmare due to its location next to the prison, and he later revealed the Governor of [[HM Prison Manchester]] had called to say it was disturbing inmates.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project went onto feature some of the most in-demand names in international house and techno music, including [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[The Chemical Brothers]] and [[Calvin Harris]] - whose appearance, Lord later went onto reveal, was a favour for an A&R at Sony. Lord revealed he put Harris ( an unknown DJ at the time) on the 21.30 slot, despite doors only opening at 22.00.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project attracted 100,000 people in its first year and has continued to sell out annually.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/sacha-lord-warehouse-project-founder-appointed-manchesters-night-time-economy-adviser-future-24-hour-clubbing-2366958#CPOiVsbVBBUvryY5.99|title=Sacha Lord: the Warehouse Project founder and Manchester\u2019s Night Time Economy Adviser on the future of the city\u2019s club scene|website=NME|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Lord and Kandel moved The Warehouse Project to Depot at the former [[Manchester Mayfield railway station]] - a move which saw it become the biggest club night in the UK with a 10,000 person capacity. The move also put it on a par with the current Guinness Book of World Records holder of the largest nightclub in the world, [[Privilege Ibiza|Privilege]] in Ibiza, which can also hold 10,000 revellers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pretty52.com/news/music-the-worlds-biggest-nightclub-is-opening-in-manchester-20190718|title=The UK's Biggest Club Night With 10,000 Capacity Is Opening In Manchester|website=pretty52.com|publisher=Pretty52}}</ref>\n\n== Parklife Festival ==\n\nLord co-created [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife Festival]] in 2010, to celebrate artists across indie, house and techno music.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> It has hosted some of the biggest names in music, including [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Liam Gallagher]] and [[Skepta]]. \n\nThe weekend festival, which moved from Platt Fields<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/parklife-festival-too-big-platt-689660|title=Festival \u2018too big\u2019 for Platt Fields|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> to Heaton Park, Manchester in 2012,<ref>http://parklifetickets.co.uk/history-of-parklife-festival/</ref> attracts 80,000 visitors each year.\n\nThe Festival employs over 4,500 people over the weekend and brings more than \u00a310million into the local economy. Each year, it raises over \u00a3100k for the Parklife Community Foundation, that is distributed to help local causes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ilovemanchester.com/how-parklife-grew-from-a-one-day-event-in-a-field-to-a-weekend-festival-bringing-in-160000-people/|title=How Parklife grew from a one day event in a field to a weekend festival bringing in 160,000 people|website=I Love MCR|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Hide Out Festival ==\n\nLord was one of the creators of Croatia\u2019s [[Hideout Festival]], a five-day alternative music extravaganza held on the island of [[Pag (island)|Pag]], Croatia, in 2011. It has sold out every single year since its conception.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political Activity ==\n\nIn 2018, Mayor of Greater Manchester, [[Andy Burnham]], appointed Lord as Greater Manchester\u2019s first Night Time Economy Adviser, following in the footsteps of [[Amy Lam\u00e9]], who was appointed by [[Mayor of London|London Mayor]] [[Sadiq Khan]] in 2016 to be the first London night czar.\n\nUnlike Lam\u00e9, who competed with 180 people for the \u00a335,000-a-year part-time role, Lord is not paid and any income created from the role has been donated directly to charity; and did not apply for the post, although it has been established that he lobbied Burnham on the importance of nightlife before the Labour politician won the inaugural mayoral elections in May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=theguardian.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe role acts to advise Burnham and the [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority]] (GMCA) on all issues relating to the night-time economy, providing a voice for workers, operators and the industry as a whole.\n\nLord has since announced a raft of recommendations to improve safety, transport and cultural diversity in the region,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.morningadvertiser.co.uk/Article/2019/08/15/Manchester-night-czar-Sacha-Lord-and-mayor-Andy-Burnham-unveil-city-blueprint|title=Manchester night czar: night time venues can revive high street|website=morningadvertiser.co.uk|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> including the introduction of later opening hours for greater accessibility and the development of night-time transport links to better serve under-represented communities on the outskirts of the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/its-time-247-transport-system-16667993|title=Mayor's night tsar calls for Greater Manchester to have 24/7 transport system|first=Jennifer|last=Williams|date=July 30, 2019|website=men}}</ref>\n\nLord has also advocated for a fair wage policy for nighttime hospitality staff, including full transparency\u00a0tipping for bar and restaurant workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/8xbvzv/can-manchesters-new-night-czar-make-tipping-fair|title=Can Manchester\u2019s New Night Czar Make Tipping Fair?|website=Vice|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Lord appeared on BBC Question Time, alongside Conservative Party chairman James Cleverly, Labour\u2019s Sarah Jones, National Farmers\u2019 Union (NFU) president Minette Batters and stand-up comedian Geoff Norcott. The transmission was the last episode to be broadcast before Britain left the European Union on 31 January 2020. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000dv70/question-time-2019-30012020|title=BBC Question Time 30 01 2020|website=BBC|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nIn 2006, [[The Warehouse Project]] was found solely responsible for an increase in drug-taking in [[HM Prison Manchester|Strangeways Prison]], leading to the event being scrutinised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aah-magazine.co.uk/2018/sacha-lord-marchionne-a-glance-at-the-man-behind-warehouse-project-parklife-and-a-key-figure-in-manchesters-nightlife|title=SACHA LORD-MARCHIONNE: A GLANCE AT THE MAN BEHIND WAREHOUSE PROJECT, PARKLIFE AND A KEY FIGURE IN MANCHESTER\u2019S NIGHTLIFE|website=Aah Magazine|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> This was because the venue was right next door and the prisoners could hear the music.\n\nIn 2012, Souvik Pal, aged 18, was ejected from a Warehouse Project event on suspicion of drug use; his body was found in nearby Bridgewater Canal 22 days later.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=Square Mile|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> In 2013, Nick Bonnie, 30, collapsed at the Warehouse Project after taking almost 15 times the standard recreational dose of [[MDMA]], and subsequently died in hospital.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=The Guardian|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLord was not directly responsible for either incident,<ref name=\"auto\"/> however, implemented drug-testing across events following the tragedies.\n\nIn 2018, Lord called for all UK clubs and festivals to have drug-testing laboratories on site,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and implemented the testing at The Warehouse Festival, which involves confiscated drugs being tested on site, and allowing alerts to be put out warning attendees of what the drugs actually are.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n== Charitable Work ==\n\nSacha Lord is patron of the Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity (charity reg number 1151518).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joshwilson.org.uk/|title=Home &#124; The Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity}}</ref>\n\nLord is also an avid campaigner on the role of mental health services for those working in the night time economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/parklife-breaks-me-sacha-lord-16039779|title='Parklife breaks me' - Sacha Lord on why night time workers need to talk about mental health|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the global Coronavirus pandemic in 2020, Lord founded the UnitedWeStream Manchester campaign<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/united-stream-goes-live-tonight-18032330|title='United We Stream goes live tonight as even more acts announced - including Hacienda night|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>, a livestream gig website which sought to raise money for the night time economy and charities in Greater Manchester through a relief fund on the website. A number of artists performed on the live stream website, including [[Roger Sanchez]] and [[Paul Oakenfold]].\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lord, Sacha}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music festival founders]]\n", "name_user": "Saw0310", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added image of subject", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacha_Lord"}
